See also \#Standard Library\# and \#Psigreturn\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("setjmp") )
#include <setjmp.h>

int setjmp( \#jmp_buf\# env );

  <env> will contain the save parameters for use by \#longjmp\#().


Function is used for error recovery.  Specifically, it stores
the register status into <env>.  \#longjmp\#() later restores these
registers (including the Stack Pointer and Program Counter), so the
computer "thinks" that setjmp() has just been called.
The only difference is the return value.

It returns 0 when called, and a value set by \#longjmp\#() when
jumping.

Note: If you call setjmp() from a function then return from that
      function before calling longjmp(), the results will be
      unpredictable.  In general, always call setjmp() from main().

See also \#Standard Library\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("raise") )
#include <signal.h>

int raise( int sig );

  <sig> is a \#signal number\# (2-89).


Function initiates the signal handler for <sig>.
It returns 0 normally.

See also \#Standard Library\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("signal") )
#include <signal.h>

\#sigfunc_t\# signal( int sig, \#sigfunc_t\# func );

  <sig> is a \#signal number\# (2-89).
  <func> is a user supplied function, or:
        SIG_DFL  abort the program (default)
        SIG_IGN  ignore the signal
        SIG_SYS  restore system signal vector
        SIG_ERR  signal error condition (bombs)


Function inserts a new signal handler.
It returns the previous signal handler (pointer).

See also \#Standard Library\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("fcvt") )
#include <stdlib.h>

char *fcvt( double value, int ndig, int *dec, int *sign );

  <value> is a floating point number.
  <ndig> is the number of digits to generate.
  <dec> returns the location of the decimal point within the
        string (may be negative or exceed ndig).
  <sign> returns the sign of <x> (0 means positive). 


Function returns a pointer to a NULL terminates string for a formated
floating point value (using the %f format).  The string contains only
the digits; no decimal point, sign or exponent.

Note: Not an ANSI function.
      Uses \#malloc\#() to allocate memory.

See also \#Standard Library\#, \#ftoa\#() and \#sprintf\#().
\end

