screen( capsensitive("GEM Version") )
GEMDOS Version Number
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... is returned by \#Sversion\#().

The low byte is reserved for 'major' version numbers.
If such a change is ever made, then it will be necessary to compare
the low byte before the high byte.  So far it has been sufficient to
compare version numbers directly.

  GEMDOS | first released with
---------+-------------------------------
  0x1300 | Mega TOS 1.02
  0x1500 | Rainbow TOS 1.04
  0x1700 | STE TOS 1.62
  0x1900 | TT TOS 3.01
  0x3000 | Falcon TOS 4.00 & MultiTOS 1.00

GEMDOS version numbers do NOT directly correspond to MiNT, TOS or AES
version numbers.

See also \#MiNT Version\#, \#TOS Version\# and \#AES Version\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("gemdos") )
#include <tos.h>

long gemdos( void, \link("%%GLOBAL%%")...\# );


Function performs a \#GEMDOS\# function call by \#GEM Opcode\#.

The argument list consists of the opcode followed by the corresponding
function arguments.  For example, one could call \#Fsfirst\#() using:

  ret = (int) gemdos(78, filename, attr);

The only difference is that \#Fsfirst\#() would push its arguments
(A0 and D0) and opcode onto the stack, perform the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")TRAP\# #1
instruction then return, whereas gemdos already has that information
on the stack.  However, it must pop its return address off the stack
and save it in a static variable before performing the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")TRAP\# #1, then
push the return address back onto the stack before returning.

(Both must save and restore register A2.)
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pterm0") )
#include <tos.h>

void Pterm0( void );


Function terminates the application, returning an error code value of
zero.  All open files are closed and all heap memory is freed.

Note: All this is handled by \#PCSTART\# using return(0) from \link("%%GLOBAL%%")main\#().

\#GEM Opcode\# 0

See also \#exit\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Cconin") )
;
#include <tos.h>

long Cconin( void )


Function returns an ASCII character (0-255) from handle 0 (\#CON\#:)

Unless redirected by \#Fforce\#(), it also returns the scan code in the
bits 16-23.
If the bit 3 of system variable 'conterm' is set, it also returns the
keyboard state in bits 24-31.

All nonstandard keys return an ASCII value of 0.

\#GEM Opcode\# 1

See also \#GEMDOS\#, \#Bconin\#(), \#Kbshift\#() and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Scan Codes\#.
\end

