screen( capsensitive("Fsetdta") )
#include <tos.h>

void Fsetdta( \#DTA\#* dta );

  <dta> is a buffer to be used to store directory info.


Function forces future calls to \#Fsfirst\#() and \#Fsnext\#() to use
the supplied \#DTA\# buffer.

This is primarily used for recursive searches through subdirectories.
By allocating a new DTA buffer for each \#Fsfirst\#()/\#Fsnext\#() search then
restoring the previous DTA, these lower level searches will not
interfere with higher level searches currently in progress.

Also, the default buffer overwrites the command line in the base page.

\#GEM Opcode\# 26

See also \#GEMDOS\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Super") )
#include <tos.h>

long Super( void* stack );

  <stack> is either 0L, 1L or the value returned by a previous call.


This function can be used to switch between user and supervisor mode:

1) If <stack> = 1L, it returns 0L if in user mode and -1L if in
   supervisor mode.  (Inquire only, no change in mode.)

2) If in user mode, use <stack> = 0L to set the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")SSP\# to equal the
   \link("%%GLOBAL%%")USP\#, or else set the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")SSP\# = <stack>.  The function returns
   the value of the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")SSP\# after the exception (which MUST be saved).

3) If in supervisor mode, set <stack> to the previously saved value
   of the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")SSP\# returned by step (2) above.  No return value.

\#GEM Opcode\# 32

See also \#GEMDOS\#, \#Supexec\#() and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Supervisor Mode\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Tgetdate") )
#include <tos.h>

unsigned int Tgetdate( void );


Function returns the current date in MS-DOS format (see \#DOSTIME\#):

year  = (Tgetdate() >> 9) + 1980;
month = (Tgetdate() >> 5) & 15;
day   = Tgetdate() & 31;

\#GEM Opcode\# 42

See also \#GEMDOS\# and \#time\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Tsetdate") )
#include <tos.h>

unsigned int Tsetdate( unsigned int date );

  <date> is the date in MS-DOS format (see \#DOSTIME\#):

     typedef union {
       unsigned int date;       /* used for the argument */
       struct {
         unsigned int year:7;   /* year since 1980       */
         unsigned int month:4;  /* month (1-12)          */
         unsigned int day:5;    /* day of month (1-31)   */
        } d;
      } DATE;


Function sets the system calendar to <date>.
Starting with \#Sversion\#() = 0x1500, it also resets the real time
clock in the keyboard.
It also resets the internal real time clock on the TT.

It returns 0 normally, or 0xFFFF on invalid date (month>12 || day>31).

\#GEM Opcode\# 43

See also \#GEMDOS\# and \#time\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Tgettime") )
#include <tos.h>

unsigned int Tgettime( void );


Function returns the current time in MS-DOS format (see \#DOSTIME\#):
Note: Time is incremented in two second intervals.

time   = Tgettime() >> 10;
month  = (Tgettime() >> 5) & 65;
second = (Tgettime() & 31) * 2;

\#GEM Opcode\# 44

See also \#GEMDOS\# and \#time\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Tsettime") )
#include <tos.h>

unsigned int Tsettime( unsigned int time );

  <time> is the time of day in MS-DOS format:

    typedef union {
      unsigned int time;       /* used as the argument  */
      struct {
        unsigned int hour:5;   /* hour of day (0-23)    */
        unsigned int minute:6; /* minute (0-59)         */
        unsigned int twosec:5; /* second/2 (0-29)       */
       } t;
     } TIME;


Function sets the system clock to <time>.
Starting with \#Sversion\#() = 0x1500, it also resets the real time
clock in the keyboard.
It also resets the internal real time clock on the TT.

It returns 0 normally, or 0xFFFF on invalid time (hour>23, etc.).

\#GEM Opcode\# 45

See also \#GEMDOS\# and \#time\#().
\end

