screen( capsensitive("Supexec") )
#include <tos.h>

long Supexec( long (*func)() );

  <func> is a user supplied function defined as:
         long func( void );


Function executes a user supplied function in \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Supervisor Mode\#.
It returns the same value returned by <func>.

Note: This approach is easier to use and safer than \#Super\#().
      The disadvantage is that you cannot make GEMDOS etc. calls from
      inside the supplied function and must pass any information using
      global or static variables.  Normally <func> is written in
      assembly language and is used to access absolute addresses.

\#XBIOS Opcode\# 38

See also \#XBIOS Misc\# and \#Super\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Puntaes") )
#include <tos.h>

void Puntaes( void );


Function releases RAM used by AES and reboots.
If AES is not RAM resident, it returns.

Note: Only the earliest Ataris did not include AES on ROM.

\#XBIOS Opcode\# 39

See also \#XBIOS Misc\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Floprate") )
#include <tos.h>

int Floprate( int devno, int newrate );

  <devno> selects the floppy drive (0 = A, !0 = B).
  <newrate> is the new seek rate code:
            0 = 6 msec
            1 = 12 msec
            2 = 2 msec
            3 = 3 msec
           -1 = keep old value


Function gets and/or sets the floppy seek rate.  It returns the old
seek rate code.

Note: Implemented starting with \#TOS Version\# 1.04
      For TOS 1.00, use system variables $A09 for A and $A0D for B.
      For TOS 1.02, use system variables $A4F for A and $A53 for B.

\#XBIOS Opcode\# 40

See also \#XBIOS I/O\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Blitmode") )
#include <tos.h>

int Blitmode( int mode );

  <mode> is the new blitter mode, or -1 to keep old value.
         0 = use software.
         1 = use blitter chip.


Function gets or sets the blitter mode.  It returns the old value:
  Bit 0  Use blitter chip (1) or software (0).
  Bit 1  Blitter chip installed (1).

Note: The BLITTER chip is used to perform bit-block transfers, which
      are used primarily for screen image manipulation.
      Blitmode() is defined even on Ataris which lack a BLITTER chip.

\#XBIOS Opcode\# 64

See also \#XBIOS Video\#, \#vro_cpyfm\#() and \#vrt_cpyfm\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("DMAread") )
#include <tos.h>

int DMAread( long sector, int count, void *buffer, int devno );

  <sector> is the (starting) logical sector number.
  <count> is the number of sectors to read.
  <buffer> is the input buffer to be filled.
  <devno> is the device identifier (NOT the drive number!):
          0-7   ASCI drives
          8-15  SCSI drives


Function reads one or more sectors from either the ACSI (DMA) or
SCSI port.

It returns 0 normally, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

Note:  ACSI drives cannot use buffers in \link("%%GLOBAL%%")TT RAM\#.
       Implemented starting with \#TOS Version\# 2.00

\#XBIOS Opcode\# 43

See also \#XBIOS I/O\# and \#Rwabs\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("DMAwrite") )
#include <tos.h>

int DMAwrite( long sector, int count, void *buffer, int devno );

  <sector> is the (starting) logical sector number.
  <count> is the number of sectors to write.
  <buffer> is the data buffer to be written.
  <devno> is the device identifier (NOT the drive number!):
          0-7   ASCI drives
          8-15  SCSI drives


Function writes one or more sectors to either the ACSI (DMA) or
SCSI port.

It returns 0 normally, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

Note:  ACSI drives cannot use buffers in \link("%%GLOBAL%%")TT RAM\#.
       Implemented starting with \#TOS Version\# 2.00

\#XBIOS Opcode\# 43

See also \#XBIOS I/O\# and \#Rwabs\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Bconmap") )
#include <tos.h>

long Bconmap( int devno );

  <devno> is the \#BIOS Device Number\# (6-9), or:
          -1 = no change (return current mapped device).
          -2 = return a pointer to the \#BCONMAP\# structure.


Function maps a device driver to \#AUX\# (device 1).
Mapping means that the jump vectors for that device are copied into
the jump vector table associated with \#AUX\#.
Also, \#Rsconf\#() and \#Iorec\#() will apply only to the currently
mapped device.

It returns the old mapped device number, or a \#BCONMAP\# structure
pointer (when <devno> = -2).

The \#BCONMAP\# structure contains the number of device drivers and
a pointer to their jump table.  (To add an additional device driver,
copy the jump table, add the new device jump vectors, increment the
number of devices and insert the new jump table pointer.)

Note: A device does not HAVE to be mapped to be used.
      Implemented starting with \#TOS Version\# 2.00

\#XBIOS Opcode\# 44

See also \#XBIOS I/O\#, \#Bconin\#(), \#Bconout\#(), \#Bconstat\#() and \#Bcostat\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("NVMaccess") )
#include <tos.h>

int NVMaccess( int opcode, int start, int count, void *buffer );

  <opcode> controls the function's operation:
           0 = copy from NVM to buffer
           1 = copy from buffer to NVM
           2 = zero the NVM and initialize the check data
  <start> is first byte in NVM to use (0-47).
  <count> is the number of bytes to copy or initialize.
  <buffer> is the I/O buffer in RAM.


Function reads or writes to the Non-Volatile Memory.
It returns 0 normally, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

Note:  Bytes 48-49 are used as a checksum.
       NVM usage is to be dictated by Atari (submit requests to be
       assigned an official byte location).
       Implemented starting with \#TOS Version\# 2.00

\#XBIOS Opcode\# 46

See also \#XBIOS Misc\#.
\end

