screen( capsensitive("AC_CLOSE") )
AC_CLOSE                                                       <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This message is sent when:
  the current application has just terminated,
  the screen is about to be cleared, or
  the window library data structures are about to be reinitialized.

The accessory should close and delete all of its windows.

  word 4 = menu id returned from \#menu_register\#().

See also \#Messages\# and \#Menu\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("AP_TERM") )
AP_TERM                                                       <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This message is sent when:
  another process has requested total control, or
  another process has requested a resolution change.

The application should immediately release all resources and
terminate.

  word 5 = reason for shutting down:
           AP_RESCHG = resolution change
           AP_TERM = other

See also \#Messages\# and \#AES_MESSAGE\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("AP_TFAIL") )
AP_TFAIL                                                       <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This message should be sent to the system when an application has
received a \#AP_TERM\# message but cannot shut down.

  word 0 = AP_TFAIL
  word 1 = application id

See also \#Messages\#, \#SWM_AESMSG\# and \#appl_write\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("SHUT_COMPLETED") )
SHUT_COMPLETED                                                 <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This message is sent when the application has requested that all other
applications shut down and the shutdown was successful.

See also \#Messages\# and \#SWM_SHUTDOWN\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("RESCH_COMPLETED") )
RESCH_COMPLETED                                                <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This message is sent when the application has requested a resolution
change.

  word 3 = status (1 = successful, 0 = unsuccessful).

See also \#Messages\# and \#SWM_REZCHANGE\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("AP_DRAGDROP") )
AP_DRAGDROP                                                    <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This message is sent when another application has initiated a drag and
drop session.

  word 4 = x location of mouse.
  word 5 = y location of mouse.
  word 6 = keyboard state:
           K_RSHIFT = right Shift
           K_LSHIFT = left Shift
           K_CNTL   = Control
           K_ALT    = Alternate
  word 7 = pipe identifier (2 byte ASCII).

See also \#Messages\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("CH_EXIT") )
CH_EXIT                                                        <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This message is sent when a child process has terminated.

  word 3 = child application id.
  word 4 = child return code.

See also \#Messages\# and \#AES_MESSAGE\#.
\end

screen( "Dialog Box" )
Dialog Box                                                     <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
A dialog box is an object tree containing various buttons and edit
fields.  The normal calling sequence to use a simple dialog box is:

int form_do_all( int tree_index, int startob, int depth )
 {
  \#OBJECT\# *tree;
  int x,y,w,h,button;

  \#rsrc_gaddr\#( R_TREE, tree_index, &tree );
  \#form_center\#( tree, &x, &y, &w, &h );
  \#form_dial\#( FMD_START, 0,0,0,0, x,y,w,h );
  \#objc_draw\#( tree, 0, depth, x,y,w,h );
  button = \#form_do\#( tree, startob );
  \#form_dial\#( FMD_FINISH, 0,0,0,0, x,y,w,h);

  tree[button].ob_state = NORMAL;   /* deselect exit button */
  return(button);
 }

More complicated dialog boxes, such as those using TOUCHEXIT objects
to implement CHECKED, OUTLINED, CROSSED or SHADOWED \#Object State\#s,
would require a more complicated calling sequence.
\end

screen( "Form Alert Format" )
Form Alert Format - \#form_alert\#()                               <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The characters '[', ']' are used to delimit the three fields:
  icon, text and buttons (in that order).
The character '|' is used to separate lines in the text field or
  buttons in the button field.
The icon field must be either '0' for no icon, '1' for a ! icon,
  '2' for a ? icon, or '3' for a STOP icon.
Max 5 lines, 3 buttons, 30 characters/line and 10 characters/button.

Examples:

"[0][This form has no icon, |three lines of text |and 1 button ][OK]"

"[1][ | |This file already exits! ][Replace|Cancel]"

"[2][Are you sure? ][Yes|No]"

"[3][Out of RAM! ][Abort]"

When an icon is used, the text will NOT be vertically centered.
To center the text, insert blank lines as in the second example.

Note: There must be at least one space between '|' characters to
      create a blank line.

Also: There is no gap between the right edge of the text field and
      the border, so include an extra blank on the end of the longest
      line of the text field for a better appearance.

See also \#sprintf\#().
\end

screen( "Window Features" )
Window Features - \#wind_create\#()                                <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
NAME    - title bar (same as drag bar but with text).
CLOSER  - close icon (enables \#WM_CLOSED\# message events).
FULLER  - full size icon (enables \#WM_FULLED\# message events).
MOVER   - drag bar (enables \#WM_MOVED\# message events).
INFO    - information bar below title (drag) bar.
SIZER   - resize icon (enables \#WM_SIZED\# message events).
UPARROW - up arrow at top of vertical scroll bar.
DNARROW - down arrow at bottom of vertical scroll bar.
VSLIDE  - vertical slider (enables \#WM_VSLID\# message events).
LFARROW - left arrow at left of horizontal scroll bar.
RTARROW - right arrow at right of horizontal scroll bar.
HSLIDE  - horizontal slider (enables \#WM_HSLID\# message events).

Arrow features enable corresponding \#WM_ARROWED\# message events.

See also \#Window Set Options\#,
\end

screen( "Window Get Options" )
Window Get Options - \#wind_get\#()                                <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
\#WF_WORKXYWH\#  - screen coordinates of current window work area
\#WF_CURRXYWH\#  - screen coordinates of current window
\#WF_PREVXYWH\#  - screen coordinates of previous window
\#WF_FULLXYWH\#  - screen coordinates of window when fulled
\#WF_HSLIDE\#    - position of horizontal slider (1-1000)
\#WF_VSLIDE\#    - position of vertical slider (1-1000)
\#WF_TOP\#       - window handle of top (active) window
\#WF_FIRSTXYWH\# - first rectangle in redraw list
\#WF_NEXTXYWH\#  - next rectangle in redraw list
\#WF_HSLSIZE\#   - size of horizontal slider (-1, 1-1000)
\#WF_VSLSIZE\#   - size of vertical slider (-1, 1-1000)
\#WF_SCREEN\#    - menu/alert screen buffers 
\#WF_COLOR\#     - \#Color Spec\# for window features.
\#WF_DCOLOR\#    - default \#Color Spec\# for window feature.
\#WF_OWNER\#     - application ID for window, open status, and rank.
\#WF_BEVENT\#    - supported window events bit flags.
\#WF_BOTTOM\#    - window handle of bottom window.
\end

screen( "Window Set Options" )
Window Set Options - \#wind_set\#()                                <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
\#WF_KIND\#      - window features
\#WF_NAME\#      - title bar text
\#WF_INFO\#      - information bar text
\#WF_CURRXYWH\#  - coordinates of current window
\#WF_HSLIDE\#    - position of horizontal slider (1-1000)
\#WF_VSLIDE\#    - position of vertical slider (1-1000)
\#WF_TOP\#       - move window to top
\#WF_NEWDESK\#   - background object tree
\#WF_HSLSIZE\#   - size of horizontal slider (-1, 1-1000)
\#WF_VSLSIZE\#   - size of vertical slider (-1, 1-1000)
\#WF_COLOR\#     - \#Color Spec\# for window features
\#WF_DCOLOR\#    - default \#Color Spec\# for window features
\#WF_BEVENT\#    - supported window events bit flags.
\#WF_BOTTOM\#    - move window to bottom.
\end

screen( capsensitive("WF_KIND") )
WF_KIND                                                        <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  int flags;    /* bit flags for \#Window Features\# */

  \#wind_set\#(handle, WF_KIND, flags);

See also \#wind_create\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("WF_NAME") )
WF_NAME                                                        <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  \#wind_set\#(handle, WF_NAME, "Title bar text field");


The text will be centered in the title (drag) bar.

Some versions of AES store the pointer value, while others store the
text.  The former require the title to be set BEFORE the window is
opened, and will change the display if the contents of the array
pointed to are changed.

See also \#Window Features\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("WF_INFO") )
WF_INFO                                                        <aes.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  \#wind_set\#(handle, WF_INFO, "Info bar text field");


The text will be left justified in the info bar.

Some versions of AES store the pointer value, while others store the
text.  The former require the title to be set BEFORE the window is
opened, and will change the display if the contents of the array
pointed to are changed.

See also \#Window Features\#.
\end

