  <child> is the array index for the object to be added.


Function modifies the ob_next, ob_head and ob_tail entries of an
\#OBJECT\# array so as to add an array element into a specific list of
sibling objects.

\#AES Opcode\# 40

See also \#Object\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("objc_delete") )
#include <aes.h>

int objc_delete( \#OBJECT\# *tree, int object );

  <tree> is the \#Object Tree\# array.
  <object> is the array index for the object to be removed.


Function modifies the ob_next, ob_head and ob_tail entries of an
\#OBJECT\# array so as to remove an array element the \#Object Tree\#.

\#AES Opcode\# 41

See also \#Object\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("objc_draw") )
#include <aes.h>

int objc_draw( \#OBJECT\# *tree, int startob, int depth,
               int xclip, int yclip, int wclip, int hclip );

  <tree> is the \#Object Tree\# array.
  <startob> is the array index for the (starting) object to be drawn.
  <depth> is the depth of child objects to be drawn:
          0 = draw <startob> only.
          1 = draw <startob> and its children only.
          ...
  <xclip> is the left edge of the clipping window (screen coordinates).
  <yclip) is the top edge of the clipping window (screen coordinates).
  <wclip> is the width of the clipping window (pixels).
  <hclip> is the height of the clipping window (pixels).


Function draws one or more objects in an object tree.  To draw an
entire object tree, use <startob> = 0 and <depth> = a large number
(3 is usually sufficient).

Only the portion of the object tree which is inside the clipping
window will be drawn.

It returns a positive number normally, or 0 on an error.

Note: objc_draw() does not combine the template and text strings of a
      formatted text object (see \#TEDINFO\#).

\#AES Opcode\# 42

See also \#Object\#, \#form_center\#() and \#form_do\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("objc_find") )
#include <aes.h>

int objc_find( \#OBJECT\# *tree, int startob, int depth,
               int mx, int my );

  <tree> is the \#Object Tree\# array.
  <startob> is the array index for the starting object for the search.
  <depth> is the depth of child objects to be searched:
          0 = check <startob> only.
          1 = check <startob> and its children only.
          ...
  <mx> is the x coordinate of the mouse.
  <my> is the y coordinate of the mouse.


Function returns the array index for the object located under the
mouse pointer (as specified by <mx> and <my>), or -1 if no object
found.

To search the entire object tree, use <startob> = 0 and <depth> = a
large number (usually 3 is sufficient).

\#AES Opcode\# 43

See also \#Object\# and \#graf_mkstate\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("objc_offset") )
#include <aes.h>

int objc_offset( \#OBJECT\# *tree, int object, int &xoff, int &yoff );

  <tree> is the \#Object Tree\# array.
  <object> is the array index for the object.
  <xoff> returns the x coordinate of the object (left edge).
  <yoff> returns the y coordinate of the object (top edge).


Function determines the screen coordinates for an object.
It returns a positive number normally, or 0 on an error.

Note: ob_x and ob_y are given relative to its parent object.

\#AES Opcode\# 44

See also \#Object\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("objc_order") )
#include <aes.h>

int objc_order( \#OBJECT\# *tree, int object, int newpos );

  <tree> is the \#Object Tree\# array.
  <object> is the array index for the object.
  <newpos> is desired position within the sibling list:
           0 = last object.
           1 = next to last object.
          -1 = first object.
          -2 = second object.
          ...


Function modifies the ob_next, ob_head and ob_tail entries of an
\#OBJECT\# array so as to relocate an object in its list of siblings.

It returns a positive number normally, or 0 on an error.

Note: The order in the \#Object Tree\# determines the order in which
      objects are drawn.

\#AES Opcode\# 45

See also \#Object\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("objc_edit") )
#include <aes.h>

int objc_edit( \#OBJECT\# *tree, int object, int edchar, int *edidx,
               int edkind );

  <tree> is the \#Object Tree\# array.
  <object> is the array index for a G_FTEXT or G_FBOXTEXT object.
  <edchar> contains a character in the low byte and the scan code
           in the high byte.
  <edidx> points to the cursor position (index) in the text field.
  <edkind> selects the operation to be performed:
           ED_INIT = combine text and template strings, turns on the
                     edit cursor and returns the initial <edidx>.
           ED_CHAR = process <edchar> and redraw.
           ED_END  = turn off edit cursor.


Function performs the various edit operations of \#form_do\#(),
one character at a time.  It can be used to replace \#form_do\#() with
\#evnt_keybd\#() or \#evnt_multi\#() interaction, or to draw FTEXT objects.

It returns a positive number normally, or 0 on an error.

Note: The original AES documentation indicated that the cursor
      position would be returned, but this was corrected later.

\#AES Opcode\# 46

See also \#Object\#, \#TEDINFO\#, \#form_keybd\#() and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Scan Codes\#.
\end

