  <big_y> is the final y coordinate for the box.
  <big_w> is the final width for the box (in pixels).
  <big_h> is the final height for the box (in pixels).


Function draws an expanding box.
It returns a positive number normally, or 0 on an error.

\#AES Opcode\# 73

See also \#Graphics\# and \#form_dial\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("graf_shrinkbox") )
#include <aes.h>

int graf_shrinkbox( int small_x, int small_y, int small_w, int small_h,
                    int big_x, int big_y, int big_w, int big_h);

  <small_x> is the final x coordinate for the box.
  <small_y> is the final y coordinate for the box.
  <small_w> is the final width for the box (in pixels).
  <small_h) is the final height for the box (in pixels).
  <big_x> is the starting x coordinate for the box.
  <big_y> is the starting y coordinate for the box.
  <big_w> is the starting width for the box (in pixels).
  <big_h> is the starting height for the box (in pixels).


Function draws an shrinking box.
It returns a positive number normally, or 0 on an error.

\#AES Opcode\# 74

See also \#Graphics\# and \#form_dial\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("graf_watchbox") )
#include <aes.h>

int graf_watchbox( \#OBJECT\# *tree, int object,
                   int in_state, int out_state);

  <tree> is the \#Object Tree\# array.
  <object> is the array index for the G_BOX object.
  <in_state> is the \#Object State\# when the mouse is in the box.
  <out_state> is the \#Object State\# when the mouse in outside the box.


Function changes the state of a G_BOX object when the mouse enters or
leaves it.  The left mouse button must be pressed before the function
is called, and it returns when the mouse button is released.

It returns a positive number normally, or 0 on an error.

\#AES Opcode\# 75

See also \#Graphics\#, \#evnt_mouse\#() and \#objc_change\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("graf_slidebox") )
#include <aes.h>

int graf_slidebox( \#OBJECT\# *tree, int parent, int object, int vh );

  <tree> is the \#Object Tree\# array.
  <parent> is the array index for the parent object for <object>.
  <object> is the array index for the sliding object.
  <vh> determines whether to slide vertically (1) or horizontally (0).


Function lets the user slide a box either vertically or horizontally.
The size and starting location of the box is taken from <object>, and
the bounding rectangle is taken from <parent>.

It returns a value between 0 and 1000 indicating the relative position
of the box inside the parent object:
  When <vl> = 0, 0=left and 1000=right.
  When <vl> = 1, 0=top and 1000=bottom.

\#AES Opcode\# 76

See also \#Graphics\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("graf_handle") )
#include <aes.h>

int graf_handle( int *wchar, int *hchar, int *wbar, int *hbar );

  <wchar> returns the character width in pixels (8,16).
  <hchar> returns the character height in pixels (8,16,32).
  <wbar> returns the bar width in pixels (11,22,19,38).
  <hbar> returns the bar height in pixels (11,19,38).


Function returns the \#VDI Handle\# for the screen workstation.

Note: The bar refers to a square box which is large enough to hold one
      character.  This is used for the height of the menu bar and the
      size of window frame bars.

\#AES Opcode\# 77

See also \#Graphics\# and \#v_opnwk\#().
\end

