screen( "GDOS" )
\#VDI\#   Graphics Device Operating System                         <vdi.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
\#vq_gdos\#         - Is GDOS loaded?
\#vq_vgdos\#        - Returns type of GDOS loaded

\#FONTGDOS\#        - Bezier Curves
\#FSMGDOS\#         - Scalable Outline Fonts
\#SpeedoGDOS\#      - 16 bit character sets

File \#ASSIGN.SYS\# on the root directory of the boot drive contains a
list of available devices and fonts.

See also \#VDI Workstation\#, \#VDI Mouse\#, \#VDI Output\#, \#VDI Attributes\#,
         \#VDI Inquire\#, \#VDI Raster\#, \#VDI Input\# and \#VDI Escapes\#.
\end

screen( "FONTGDOS" )
FONTGDOS                                                       <vdi.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
\#v_bez\#           - Draw Bezier
\#v_bez_fill\#      - Draw filled Bezier

\#v_bez_on\#        - Enable Bezier splines
\#v_bez_off\#       - Disable Bezier splines
\#v_bez_qual\#      - Set Bezier depth
\#v_set_app_buff\#  - Allocate new Bezier buffer

A Bezier is defined using two anchor points followed by two control
points.  It creates a curved polyline which passes through the anchor
points (x0,y0) and (x3,y3) and is tangent to the lines connecting the
anchor points to their respective control points (x1,y1) and (x2,y2).

x = (((ax*t + bx)*t + cx)*t + x0
y = (((ay*t + by)*t + cy)*t + y0

cx = 3*(x1 - x0)           cy = 3*(y1 - y0)
bx = 3*(x2 - x1) - cx      by = 3*(y2 - y1) - cy
ax = x3 - x0 - bx - cx     ay = y3 - y0 - by - cy

FONTGDOS (like plain GDOS) supports only bitmap fonts.
\end

screen( "FSMGDOS" )
FSMGDOS (Scalable Font Manager \#GDOS\#)                           <vdi.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
\#v_flushcache\#   - flush bitmap cache
\#v_ftext\#        - write text using remainders
\link("FSM v_getoutline")v_getoutline\#   - return scalable character definition
\link("FSM v_killoutline")v_killoutline\#  - release memory for outline definition
\#v_loadcache\#    - load previously save bitmaps
\#v_savecache\#    - save bitmap cache to disk

\#vqt_advance\#    - returns offset to next character
\#vqt_cachesize\#  - return free cache space
\#vqt_devinfo\#    - return device driver availability and name
\#vqt_f_extent\#   - returns bounding rectangle 
\#vqt_get_tables\# - return ASCII conversion tables

\#vst_arbpt\#      - set cell height to arbitrary point size
\#vst_error\#      - turn on/off error message
\#vst_scratch\#    - set effects buffer allocation mode
\#vst_setsize\#    - set cell width to arbitrary point size
\#vst_skew\#       - set text slant to given angle

Scalable fonts are rarely an even number of rasters in size.  These
functions keep track of the remainder when placing characters on the
screen.

FSMGDOS also supports all \#FONTGDOS\# funtions.
\end

screen( "SpeedoGDOS" )
SpeedoGDOS                                                     <vdi.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
\#v_ftext_offset\#   - specify array of character offsets
\#v_getbitmap_info\# - return information about bitmapped fonts
\#v_getoutline\#     - return scalable character definition
\#v_killoutline\#    - not used by SpeedoGDOS

\#vqt_advance32\#    - return offset to next character
\#vqt_fontheader\#   - return font header and TDF file
\#vqt_get_table\#    - return ASCII/Bitstream font mapping
\#vqt_pairkern\#     - return character kerning adjustment
\#vqt_trackkern\#    - return track kerning adjustment

\#vst_arbpt32\#      - set cell height to fractional point size
\#vst_charmap\#      - select Atari or Bitstream character map
\#vst_kern\#         - set kerning adjustments
\#vst_setsize32\#    - set cell width to fractional point size

See also \#fix31\#, \#Kerning\# and \#Speedo Font Header\#.

SpeedoGDOS implements all \#FONTGDOS\# and \#FSMGDOS\# functions, although
it sometimes uses different bindings for the same \#VDI Opcode\#.
\end

screen( "VDI Handle" )
\#VDI\# Graphics Handle
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Each workstation (or virtual workstation) is assigned a handle when
opened.

The handle for the screen is returned by \#graf_handle\#().
The handle for other devices is returned by \#v_opnwk\#().
The handle for a virtual workstation is returned by \#v_opnvwk\#().

Every other VDI graphics function refers to this handle.

The handle not only identifies the device, it is associated with the
current settings for the \#VDI Coordinates\# and attributes.
\end

screen( "VDI Coordinates" )
\#VDI\# Coordinates
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Raster Coordinates (RC) refer to the smallest physical unit handled by
  the device.  The upper left corner corresponds to 0,0 and the lower
  right corner coordinates are device (and resolution) dependent.

Normalized Device Coordinates (NDC) always vary between 0 and 32767
  for both vertical and horizontal coordinates.  The lower left hand
  corner corresponds to 0,0 and the upper right hand corner
  corresponds to 32767,32767.  (Not supported by the screen.)

Note: VDI functions define rectangles in terms of corners rather than
      the (x,y,w,h) units used by \#AES\# functions.

Also: Angles are defined in units of 0.1 degrees:       900
                                                         |
                                                   1800-- -- 0
                                                         |
                                                       2700
See also \#VDI Description\#.
\end

screen( "VDI Description" )
\#VDI\# Workstation Description Array
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Functions \#v_opnwk\#(), \#v_opnvwk\#() and \#vq_extnd\#() return a 57 element
int array containing the following:

 [0] Maximum horizontal coordinate value.
 [1] Maximum vertical coordinate value.
 [2] \#VDI Coordinates\# (0 = RC, 1 = NDC).
 [3] Width of pixel in microns (0.000001 meter).
 [4] Height of pixel in microns (0.000001 meter).

 [5] Number of text font heights (0 = scalable, see \#vst_height\#).
 [6] Number of line types (see \#vsl_type\#).
 [7] Number of line widths (0 = scalable, see \#vsl_width\#).
 [8] Number of marker symbols (see \#vsm_type\#).
 [9] Number of marker sizes (0 = scalable, see \#vsm_height\#).
[10] Number of text fonts (see \#vst_font\#).
[11] Number of fill patterns (see \#vsf_style\#).
[12] Number of crosshatch patterns (see \#vsf_style\#).
[13] Number of color indexes for device (see \#vs_color\#).

[14] Number of Generalize Drawing Primitives (GDP).
[15-24] List of available GDP codes:
        1 = \#v_bar\#().
        2 = \#v_arc\#().
        3 = \#v_pieslice\#().
        4 = \#v_circle\#().
        5 = \#v_ellipse\#().
        6 = \#v_ellarc\#().
        7 = \#v_ellpie\#().
        8 = \#v_rbox\#().
        9 = \#v_rfbox\#().
       10 = \#v_justified\#().
       -1 = end of list.
[25-34] \#VDI Attributes\# used by the above GDP's (in the same order):
        0 = line attributes (vsl_... ).
        1 = marker attributes (vsm_... ).
        2 = text attributes (vst_... ).
        3 = fill attributes (vsf_... ).
        4 = none.

[35] Color device (1) or monochrome (0).
[36] Text can be rotated (1) or not (0).  (See \#vst_rotation\#).
[37] \#v_contourfill\#() available (1) or not (0).
[38] \#v_cellarray\#() available (1) or not (0).
[39] Number of RGB colors possible (2 - 32767):
     0 = more than 32767.
     1 = monochrome.
[40] Number of locator devices supported:
     1 = keyboard only.
     2 = mouse or tablet.
[41] Number of valuator devices supported:
     1 = keyboard only.
     2 = other device?
[42] Number of choice devices supported:
     1 = keyboard only.
     2 = mouse buttons.
[43] Number of string devices supported (1 = keyboard).
[44] Workstation type:
     0 = output only.
     1 = input only.
     2 = input & output.
     3 = reserved.
     4 = metafile (output).

[45] Minimum character width (see \#vst_height\#).
[46] Minimum character height.
[47] Maximum character width.
[48] Maximum character height.

[49] Minimum line width (see \#vsl_width\#).
[50] reserved (0)
[51] Maximum line width.
[52] reserved (0)

[53] Minimum marker width (see \#vsm_height\#).
[54] Minimum marker height.
[55] Maximum marker width.
[56] Maximum marker height.

See also \#VDI Extended\#.
\end

screen( "VDI Extended" )
\#VDI\# Extended Inquire Array
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Functions \#vq_extnd\#() returns a 57 element int array containing the
following:

 [0] Type of screen:
     0 = not a screen.
     1 = separate alpha & graphics controllers with separate screens.
     2 = separate alpha & graphics controllers with common screen.
     3 = common alpha & graphics with separate image memory.
     4 = common alpha & graphics with common image memory (normal).
 [1] Number of background colors available on palette.
 [2] Text Effects Supported:
      1 = boldface (thick)
      2 = light (shaded)
      4 = italics (slanted)
      8 = underlined
     16 = outlined
 [3] Raster scaling allowed (1) or not (0).  (See \#VDI Raster\#)
 [4] Number of color bit planes (see \#vro_cpyfm\#).
 [5] Color lookup table supported (1) or not (0). (See \#vs_color\#)
 [6] Number of 16x16 raster operations per second.
 [7] Contour fill supported (1) or not (0).  (See \#v_contourfill\#)
 [8] Character rotation supported (see \#vst_rotation\#):
     0 = none
     1 = 90 degree increments (normal)
     2 = all angles
 [9] Number of writing modes available (see \#vswr_mode\#).
[10] Input modes available (see \#vsin_mode\#):
     0 = none
     1 = request mode only
     2 = request and sample mode
[11] Text alignment supported (1) on not (0).  (See \#vst_alignment\#)
[12] Inking supported (1) or not (0).
[13] Rubberbanding supported (1) or not (0).
[14] Maximum number of polygon vertices (-1 = no limit).
[15] Maximum intin array size (-1 = no limit).
     Note: Pure C uses a 128 element array (see \#GEMPARBLK\#).
[16] Number of mouse buttons (2).
[17] Are line styles available for wide lines (1) or not (0).
[18] Writing modes available for wide lines.

[19-56] Reserved (contains zeros).

See also \#VDI Description\#.
\end

screen( "Raster Mode" )
\#VDI Raster\# Modes                                               <vdi.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
S = Source \#MFDB\#, D = Destination \#MFDB\#

S_ONLY     - copy source to destination (replace mode)
ALL_WHITE  - write zeros to destination
ALL_BLACK  - write ones to destination
D_ONLY     - no change
D_INVERT   - XOR D

The following are best when used with single bit plane images:

S_AND_D    - mask source with destination
NOTS_AND_D - mask source background with destination
S_AND_NOTD - mask source with destination background
S_OR_D     - merge source with destination
NOTS_OR_D  - merge source background with destination
S_OR_NOTD  - merge source with destination background
S_XOR_D    - either source or destination, but not both
NOT_D      - destination background
NOT_SANDD  - background of S_AND_D
NOT_SORD   - background of S_OR_D
NOT_SXORD  - background of S_XOR_D
\end

screen( "Bit Planes" )
\#VDI Raster\# Bit Planes
----------------------------------------------------------------------
A standard format raster image consists of an array of single bit
plane images (each image must be word aligned):
  int raster[x_word][y_line][bit_plane]

The screen raster image consists of interleafed words (16 bits) of
image data:
  int raster[bit_plane][x_word][y_line]

color    | index | 4 planes | 2 planes |
---------+-------+----------+----------+
WHITE    |   0   | 0000 = 0 |  00 = 0  |
BLACK    |   1   | 1111 = F |  11 = 3  |
RED      |   2   | 0001 = 1 |  01 = 1  |
GREEN    |   3   | 0010 = 2 |  10 = 2  |
BLUE     |   4   | 0100 = 4 |
CYAN     |   5   | 0110 = 6 |
YELLOW   |   6   | 0011 = 3 |
MAGENTA  |   7   | 0101 = 5 |
LWHITE   |   8   | 0111 = 7 |
LBLACK   |   9   | 1000 = 8 |
LRED     |  10   | 1001 = 9 |
LGREEN   |  11   | 1010 = A |
LBLUE    |  12   | 1100 = C |
LCYAN    |  13   | 1110 = E |
LYELLOW  |  14   | 1011 = B |
LMAGENTA |  15   | 1101 = D |
\end

screen( "Kerning" )
Kerning
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Track kerning adjust the (minimum) spacing between characters.
\#SpeedoGDOS\# implements three types of track kerning: normal, tight,
and extra tight.

Pair kerning adjusts the spacing between specific pairs of characters.
For example, the characters "//" would appear too far apart using
normal spacing, whereas "/\\" would appear too close together.

\#vst_kern\#() turns kerning on or off.

\#vqt_pairkern\#() returns the adjustment for a specific pair.
\#vqt_trackkern\#() returns the global kerning adjustment.
\end

screen( "VDI Device" )
VDI Device Numbers
----------------------------------------------------------------------
These numbers are assigned to GDOS device drivers by \#ASSIGN.SYS\#.

Screen:     1 - 10
Plotters:  11 - 20
Printers:  21 - 30
Metafiles: 31 - 40
Cameras:   41 - 50
Tablets:   51 - 60
Memory:    61 - 70 (see \#Memory Driver\#)

Screen drivers (in ROM):
  1  (default)
  2  (ST Low Res)
  3  (ST Med Res)
  4  (ST High Res)
    6  (TT Med Res)
  8  (TT High Res)
  9  (TT Low Res)

See also \#v_opnwk\#(), \#v_opnvwk\#() and \#Getrez\#().
\end

screen( "ASSIGN.SYS" )
ASSIGN.SYS File Format
----------------------------------------------------------------------
If the first line starts with "PATH = ", this line is used to locate
the folder containing the device and font files.

Lines beginning with a number are \#VDI Device\# drivers.

Remaining lines are font filenames to be used by the preceding driver.
  (Speedo fonts are automatically loaded.)

Everything after a ';' in a line is ignored (comment).  Blank and
purely comment lines are allowed.

'P' is used to indicate that the driver is in ROM.
'R' is used to indicate that the driver should remain RAM resident.

See also \#vst_load_fonts\#().
\end

screen( "Memory Driver" )
Memory Driver
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... performs graphics operations to a 1 bit plane raster image.  This
image can then be copied to other devices or buffers using \#vrt_cpyfm\#().
\#v_updwk\#() clears the buffer.

Using a raster buffer can significantly speed up window refresh
operations.  However, only one Memory Device can be open at a time.

The \#v_opnwk\#() binding is not sufficient to open a memory device.
Instead use:

#include <vdi.h>

VDIPB vdipb = {_VDIParBlk.contrl, _VDIParBlk.intin, _VDIParBlk.ptsin,
  _VDIParBlk.intout, _VDIParBlk.ptsout};

/* v_opnmwk() returns a pointer to the raster buffer */

void* v_opnmwk( int *work_in, int *handle, int *work_out,
  int width,     /* width of raster image in pixels  */
  int height)    /* height of raster image in pixels */
 {
  int i;
  long retval;

  vdipb.ptsin[0] = width - 1;
  vdipb.ptsin[1] = height - 1;
  vdipb.contrl[0] = 1;          /* op-code */
  vdipb.contrl[1] = 1;          /* number points input */
  vdipb.contrl[3] = 11;         /* number intin parameters */
  for(i=0; i<11; i++) vdipb.intin[i] = work_in[i];

  vdi(&vdipb);

  *handle = vdipb.contrl[6];
  for(i=0; i<45; i++) work_out[i] = vdipb.intout[i];
  for(i=0; i<13; i++) work_out[45+i] = vdipb.ptsout[i];

  retval = ((long) vdipb.contrl[0] << 16) | vdipb.contrl[1];
  return( (void*) retval );
 }
\end

screen( capsensitive("vdi") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vdi( \#VDIPB\# *vdipb );

  <vdipb> is used to pass all input and output parameters.
          It can be initialized as a global or static variable:

\#VDIPB\# vdipb = {_VDIParBlk.contrl, _VDIParBlk.intin, _VDIParBlk.ptsin,
               _VDIParBlk.intout, _VDIParBlk.ptsout};

(You don't HAVE to use the arrays in \#_VDIParBlk\#.)

Function can be used to create new VDI bindings.  The opcodes and
numbers of input and output parameters are stored in vdipd.contrl[].
You will also need to know the exact order in which the input and
output parameters are packed into the arrays, and everything must be
converted into \link("%%GLOBAL%%")int\#s.

For examples, see \#Memory Driver\#, \#v_ftext16\#() and \#v_ftext_offset bugfix\#.

See also \#VDI Control Array\#.
\end

screen( "v_ftext16" )
#include <vdi.h>

VDIPB vdipb = {_VDIParBlk.contrl, _VDIParBlk.intin, _VDIParBlk.ptsin,
  _VDIParBlk.intout, _VDIParBlk.ptsout};

/* v_ftext16() writes text to the screen using 16 bit indexes */
/* see also \#vst_charmap\#()                                     */

void v_ftext16(
  int handle,      /* workstation handle */
  int x,           /* starting x coordinate */
  int y,           /* starting y corrdinate */
  int *text,       /* array of 16 bit character indexes */
  int len)         /* number of characters in text[] */
 {
  int i;

  vdipb.contrl[0] = 241;     /* op-code */
  vdipb.contrl[1] = 1;       /* number of points input */
  vdipb.contrl[3] = len;     /* number of intin entries */
  vdipb.contrl[6] = handle;

  vdipd.ptsin[0] = x;
  vdipd.ptsin[1] = y;
    
  for(i=0; i<len; i++) vdipb.intin[i] = text[i];

  vdi(&vdipb);
 }
\end

screen( capsensitive("v_opnwk") )
#include <vdi.h>

void v_opnwk( int *work_in, int *handle, int *work_out );

  <work_in> is an 11 entry int array containing default attributes:
            [0] = \#VDI Device\# number (1 for screen).
            [1] = line type (see \#vsl_type\#)
            [2] = line color index (see \#vsl_color\#)
            [3] = marker type (see \#vsm_type\#)
            [4] = marker color index (see \#vsm_color\#)
            [5] = text face (see \#vst_font\#)
            [6] = text color index (see \#vst_color\#)
            [7] = fill interior style (see \#vsf_interior\#)
            [8] = fill style index (see \#vsf_style\#)
            [9] = fill color index (see \#vsf_color\#)
           [10] = \#VDI Coordinates\#:
                  0 = map full NDC space to full RC space.
                  2 = use Raster Coordinates (RC).

  <handle> returns the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")VDI handle\# for the physical device.
  <work_out> is a 57 entry int array to return the \#VDI Description\#.


Function opens a physical device using a GDOS device driver.
The only device supported on ROM is the screen, and it is already
open.

Note: It will crash if GDOS is not loaded.

\#VDI Opcode\# 1

See also \#VDI Workstation\#, \#graf_handle\#(), \#vqt_devinfo\#() and \#Memory Driver\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("v_opnvwk") )
#include <vdi.h>

void v_opnvwk( int *work_in, int *handle, int *work_out );

  <work_in> is an 11 entry int array containing default attributes:
            [0] = \#VDI Device\# number (1 for screen).
            [1] = line type (see \#vsl_type\#)
            [2] = line color index (see \#vsl_color\#)
            [3] = marker type (see \#vsm_type\#)
            [4] = marker color index (see \#vsm_color\#)
            [5] = text face (see \#vst_font\#)
            [6] = text color index (see \#vst_color\#)
            [7] = fill interior style (see \#vsf_interior\#)
            [8] = fill style index (see \#vsf_style\#)
            [9] = fill color index (see \#vsf_color\#)
           [10] = \#VDI Coordinates\#:
                  0 = map full NDC space to full RC space.
                  2 = use RC (Raster Coordinates).

  <handle> must contain the \#VDI Handle\# for an open graphics device
           on entry.
           It returns the \#VDI Handle\# for the virtual workstation,
           or 0 if unable to open.

  <work_out> is a 57 entry int array to return the \#VDI Description\#.


Function opens a virtual device workstation.

Each virtual workstation maintains a separate set of attributes.

\#VDI Opcode\# 100

See also \#VDI Workstation\#.
\end

