              16x16 bit maps of the fill pattern.  The first entry
              contains the bit map for the top row, etc.
  <planes> is the number of color planes (usually 1).  Multiple plane
           patterns must be written in MD_REPLACE mode (see \#vswr_mode\#).


Function creates a user defined fill pattern to be used with the
FIS_USER fill style (see \#vsf_interior\#).

\#VDI Opcode\# 112

See also \#VDI Attributes\#, \#v_bar\#(), \#v_circle\#(), \#v_contourfill\#(), \#v_ellipse\#(),
         \#v_ellpie\#(), \#v_fillarea\#(), \#v_pieslice\#(), \#v_rfbox\#() and \#vr_recfl\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vro_cpyfm") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vro_cpyfm( int handle, int wr_mode, int *pxyarray,
                \#MFDB\# *psrcMFDB, \#MFDB\# *pdesMFDB );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <wr_mode> is the \#Raster Mode\#.
  <pxyarray> is an 8 entry int array of \#VDI Coordinates\#:
             [0] = left (or right) x coordinate of source rectangle.
             [1] = lower (or upper) y coordinate of source rectangle.
             [2] = right (or left) x coordinate of source rectangle.
             [3] = upper (or lower) y coordinate of source rectangle.
             [4] = left (or right) x coordinate of dest rectangle.
             [5] = lower (or upper) y coordinate of dest rectangle.
             [6] = right (or left) x coordinate of dest rectangle.
             [7] = upper (or lower) y coordinate of dest rectangle.
  <psrcMFDB> points to the source Memory Form Definition Block.
  <pdesMFDB> points to the destination Memory Form Definition Block.


Function copies the source raster to the destination (S_ONLY), or
performs any of the other 15 possible \#Raster Mode\# operations.

One selects the physical device to be either the source or the
destination by setting the corresponding \#MFDB\# fd_addr to NULL.

If the source and destination rectangles are not the same size, VDI
will use the size from the source and only the upper left corner of
the destination.

\#VDI Opcode\# 109

See also \#VDI Raster\# and \#Bit Planes\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vrt_cpyfm") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vrt_cpyfm( int handle, int wr_mode, int *pxyarray,
                \#MFDB\# *psrcMFDB, \#MFDB\# *pdesMFDB, int *color_index );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <wr_mode> is the writing mode:
            MD_REPLACE - replace foreground and background
            MD_TRANS   - replace foreground only
            MD_XOR     - change foreground to reverse video of old image
            MD_ERASE   - replace background only
  <pxyarray> is an 8 entry int array of \#VDI Coordinates\#:
             [0] = left (or right) x coordinate of source rectangle.
             [1] = lower (or upper) y coordinate of source rectangle.
             [2] = right (or left) x coordinate of source rectangle.
             [3] = upper (or lower) y coordinate of source rectangle.
             [4] = left (or right) x coordinate of dest rectangle.
             [5] = lower (or upper) y coordinate of dest rectangle.
             [6] = right (or left) x coordinate of dest rectangle.
             [7] = upper (or lower) y coordinate of dest rectangle.
  <psrcMFDB> points to the source Memory Form Definition Block.
  <pdesMFDB> points to the destination Memory Form Definition Block.
  <color_index> is a 2 entry int array of color indexes:
                [0] = foreground color.
                [1] = background color.


Function copies a 1 bit plane source raster to a color destination
raster using the foreground and background colors in <color_index>.

One selects the physical device to be the destination by setting the
corresponding \#MFDB\# fd_addr to NULL.

If the source and destination rectangles are not the same size, VDI
will use the size from the source and only the upper left corner of
the destination.

\#VDI Opcode\# 121

See also \#VDI Raster\# and \#Bit Planes\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vr_trnfm") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vr_trnfm( int handle, \#MFDB\# *psrcMFDB, \#MFDB\# *pdesMFDB );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <psrcMFDB> points to the source Memory Form Definition Block.
  <pdesMFDB> points to the destination Memory Form Definition Block.


Function transforms between standard and device specific formats.
It sets pdesMFDB->fd_stand to be the opposite of the source format.

\#VDI Opcode\# 110

See also \#VDI Raster\# and \#Bit Planes\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("v_get_pixel") )
#include <vdi.h>

void v_get_pixel( int handle, int x, int y, int *pel, int *index );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <x> is the pixel x coordinate (see \#VDI Coordinates\#).
  <y> is the pixel y coordinate.
  <pel> returns the pixel value (bit planes used).
  <index> returns the pixel color index.


Function returns the color for a given pixel.

\#VDI Opcode\# 105

See also \#VDI Raster\# and  \#v_pmarker\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vsin_mode") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vsin_mode( int handle, int dev_type, int mode );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <dev_type> is the input device type:
             1 = locator (mouse or tablet)
             2 = valuator (optional)
             3 = choice (function keys)
             4 = string (keyboard)
  <mode> is the input mode:
         1 = request (wait for event)
         2 = sample (return current state)


Function sets the input mode for an input device.

There is no inherit difference between vrq_... and vsm_... functions.
The description for vrq_... functions is how both will behave when in
request mode, and the description for vsm_... functions is how both
will behave in sample mode.

Not all devices support all (or any) input modes (See \#VDI Extended\#).
The screen driver in ROM supports both modes.

Warning: Sample mode functions are almost useless due to slowness.
         One can improve the speed by writing special bindings
         using \#vdi\#().

\#VDI Opcode\# 33

See also \#VDI Input\#, \#VDI Description\# and \#vqin_mode\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vrq_locator") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vrq_locator( int handle, int x, int y, int *xout, int *yout,
                  int *term );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <x> is the starting x coordinate.
  <y> is the starting y coordinate.
  <xout> returns the final x coordinate.
  <yout> returns the final y coordinate.
  <term> returns the terminating event:
         For keyboard event, ASCII value in low byte.
         For button event, 32 + button.


Function turns on the cursor (mouse form) at the given coordinates,
tracks the locator input until the terminating event (keyboard or
button), then turns off the cursor and returns.

Note: Device must be set for request mode (see \#vsin_mode\#).
      The first time it is called it might return immediately with
      a phantom button event.

\#VDI Opcode\# 28

See also \#VDI Input\# and \#VDI Coordinates\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vsm_locator") )
#include <vdi.h>

int vsm_locator( int handle, int x, int y, int *xout, int *yout,
                 int *term );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <x> is the starting x coordinate.
  <y> is the starting y coordinate.
  <xout> returns the new x coordinate (if changed).
  <yout> returns the new y coordinate (if changed).
  <term> returns a keyboard or button event (no queue):
         For keyboard event, ASCII value.
         For button event, 32 + button.


Function moves the cursor (mouse form) to the given location, then
returns the updated location caused by any motion during the time
required to redraw the mouse.

Its return value indicates the following:
  0 = no coordinate change or event.
  1 = new mouse coordinates.
  2 = terminating event detected.
  3 = coordinate change and event detected.

Note: Device must be set for sample mode (see \#vsin_mode\#).
      Cursor (mouse form) must be already visible (see \#v_dspcur\#).

\#VDI Opcode\# 28

See also \#VDI Input\#, \#VDI Coordinates\# and \#graf_mkstate\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vrq_valuator") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vrq_valuator( int handle, int valuator_in, int *valuator_out,
                   int *term );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <valuator_in> is the starting value (1-100).
  <valuator_out> returns the final value (1-100).
  <term> returns a keyboard or button event:
         For keyboard event, ASCII value.
         For button event, 32 + button.


Function allows the user to modify the "valuator."
This function may not be available on all devices.
It is NOT supported by the screen driver in ROM.

Note: Device must be set for request mode (see \#vsin_mode\#).

\#VDI Opcode\# 29

See also \#VDI Input\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vsm_valuator") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vsm_valuator( int handle, int val_in, int *val_out, int *term,
                   int *status );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <val_in> is the old value (1-100).
  <val_out> returns the new value (1-100).
  <term> returns a keyboard or button event:
         For keyboard event, ASCII value.
         For button event, 32 + button.
  <status> returns the following:
           0 = nothing happened.
           1 = valuator changed.
           2 = terminating event.


Function samples the "valuator."
This function may not be available on all devices.
It is NOT supported by the screen driver in ROM.

Note: Device must be set for sample mode (see \#vsin_mode\#).

\#VDI Opcode\# 29

See also \#VDI Input\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vrq_choice") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vrq_choice( int handle, int ch_in, int *ch_out );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <ch_in> is the default value (1 - max).
  <ch_out> returns the new value (1 - max).


Function waits for a key press.
If the key is a valid choice key, it returns the new value.
Otherwise it returns <ch_in>.

This function may not be available on all devices.
It is NOT supported by the screen driver in ROM.

Note: Device must be set for request mode (see \#vsin_mode\#).

\#VDI Opcode\# 30

See also \#VDI Input\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vsm_choice") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vsm_choice( int handle, int *choice );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <choice> returns the choice value (1 - max).


Function waits for a key press.
If the key is a valid choice key, it returns the new value.
Otherwise it returns the default value.

This function may not be available on all devices.
The screen driver in ROM always returns 1.

Note: Device must be set for sample mode (see \#vsin_mode\#).

\#VDI Opcode\# 30

See also \#VDI Input\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vrq_string") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vrq_string( int handle, int max_length, int echo_mode,
                 int *echo_xy, char *string );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <max_length> is the maximum string length.  A negative value will
               put the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Scan Codes\# into the high byte of the intout 
               array elements (see \#GEMPARBLK\#).
  <echo_mode> turn the screen echo on (1) or off (0).
  <echo_xy> is a 2 entry int array containing:
            [0] = starting x coordinate for echo.
            [1] = starting y coordinate for echo.
  <string> is a buffer array to return a NULL terminated string.
           It must be at least <max_length> + 1 bytes long.


Function allows the user to type in a string.  It returns when the
RETURN key is pressed.

Echoing may not be available on all devices.
Echoing is NOT supported by the screen driver in ROM.

Note: Device must be set for request mode (see \#vsin_mode\#).

\#VDI Opcode\# 31

See also \#VDI Input\#, \#v_gtext\#() and \#evnt_keybd\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vsm_string") )
#include <vdi.h>

int vsm_string( int handle, int max_length, int echo_mode,
                int *echo_xy, char *string );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <max_length> is the maximum string length (1).  A negative value
               will put the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Scan Codes\# into the high byte of the
               intout[0] (see \#GEMPARBLK\#).
  <echo_mode> turn the screen echo on (1) or off (0).
  <echo_xy> is a 2 entry int array containing:
            [0] = x coordinate for echo.
            [1] = y coordinate for echo.
  <string> is a 2 entry char array to return:
           [0] = ASCII character.
           [1] = NULL.


Function returns the last character typed.
Its return value is 0 if no ASCII key was pressed since the last call.

Echoing may not be available on all devices.
Echoing is NOT supported by the screen driver in ROM.

Note: Device must be set for sample mode (see \#vsin_mode\#).

\#VDI Opcode\# 31

See also \#VDI Input\#, \#v_gtext\#() and \#evnt_keybd\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vsc_form") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vsc_form( int handle, int *pcur_form );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <pcur_form> is a cursor (mouse) form definition.  It is typed as an
              int array, but is identical to an \#MFORM\# structure.


Function re-defines the mouse form.

\#VDI Opcode\# 111

See also \#VDI Input\# and \#graf_mouse\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vex_timv") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vex_timv( int handle, int (*tim_addr)(), int (**otim_addr)(),
               int *tim_conv );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <tim_addr> is an interrupt handler (usually written in assembly).
             It should terminate with an \link("%%GLOBAL%%")RTS\# instruction, or \link("%%GLOBAL%%")JMP\# to
             old interrupt handler.
  <otim_addr> returns the old timer handler address.
  <tim_conv> returns the time interval between ticks in msec (5). 


Function replaces the system timer interrupt vector.

\#VDI Opcode\# 118

See also \#VDI Input\#, \#Setexc\#() and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")etv_timer\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("v_show_c") )
#include <vdi.h>

void v_show_c( int handle, int reset );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <reset> makes the cursor visible unconditionally (0), or only if the
          number of calls to v_show_c() equals the number of calls to
          \#v_hide_c\#().


Function causes the cursor (mouse form) to become visible.

\#VDI Opcode\# 122

See also \#VDI Input\#, \#v_dspcur\#() and \#graf_mouse\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("v_hide_c") )
#include <vdi.h>

void v_hide_c( int handle );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.


Function causes the cursor (mouse form) to become invisible.

Note: Moving the mouse consists of restoring a previously saved
      raster image at the old mouse position, then re-drawing the
      mouse form at the new location.
      If the mouse is visible while performing VDI graphics, then when
      the mouse is moved, the changes will be lost when the old raster
      image is restored.

\#VDI Opcode\# 123

See also \#VDI Input\#, \#v_rmcur\#() and \#graf_mouse\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vq_mouse") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vq_mouse( int handle, int *pstatus, int *x, int *y );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <pstatus> returns the mouse buttons state:
            0 = both buttons up
            1 = left button down
            2 = right button down
            3 = both buttons down
  <x> returns the x coordinate of the mouse in \#VDI Coordinates\#.
  <y> returns the y coordinate of the mouse in \#VDI Coordinates\#.


Function returns the mouse status and position.

\#VDI Opcode\# 124

See also \#VDI Input\# and \#graf_mkstate\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vex_butv") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vex_butv( int handle, int (*pusrcode)(), int (**psavcode)() );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <pusrcode> is a button event handler (usually written in assembly).
             It should terminate with an \link("%%GLOBAL%%")RTS\# instruction.
             D0 will contain the button state (see \#vq_mouse\#), and
             is used to return the button state when done.
  <psavcode> returns the old button event handler.


Function inserts a new button event handler.  It is called every
time the mouse button state changes.  It was intended to allow the
mouse button state to be manipulated (e.g.; swap left & right buttons).

\#VDI Opcode\# 125

See also \#VDI Input\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vex_motv") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vex_motv( int handle, int (*pusrcode)(), int (**psavcode)() );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <pusrcode> is a mouse movement handler (usually written in assembly).
             It should terminate with an \link("%%GLOBAL%%")RTS\# instruction.
             D0 and D1 will contain the x and y coordinates
             (respectively), and will be used to return these
             coordinates when done.
  <psavcode> returns the old mouse movement handler.


Function inserts a new mouse movement handler.  It is called
every time the mouse position changes.  It was intended to allow the
mouse position to be manipulated.

\#VDI Opcode\# 126

See also \#VDI Input\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vex_curv") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vex_curv( int handle, int (*pusrcode)(), int (**psavcode)() );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <pusrcode> is a cursor form handler (usually written in assembly).
             It should terminate with an \link("%%GLOBAL%%")RTS\# instruction.
             D0 and D1 will contain the x and y coordinates
             (respectively) for the cursor to be drawn.
  <psavcode> returns the old mouse movement handler.


Function inserts a new cursor drawing handler.  It is called
every time the cursor is to be drawn.

Note: If the new handler merely changes the x,y location used, it
      can perform a \link("%%GLOBAL%%")JSR\# or \link("%%GLOBAL%%")JMP\# to the old handler.

\#VDI Opcode\# 127

See also \#VDI Input\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vq_key_s") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vq_key_s( int handle, int *pstatus );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <pstatus> returns the keyboard state (bit flags):
            K_RSHIFT = right Shift
            K_LSHIFT = left Shift
            K_CNTL   = Control
            K_ALT    = Alternate


Function returns information about the keyboard, such as whether the
SHIFT key is being pressed.

\#VDI Opcode\# 128

See also \#VDI Input\#, \#graf_mkstate\#() and \#Kbshift\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vq_extnd") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vq_extnd( int handle, int owflag, int *work_out );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <owflag> selects whether to return the \#VDI Description\# (0) or
           the \#VDI Extended\# information (1).
  <work_out> is a 57 entry int array used to return the selected info.


Function returns extended information about the workstation.

\#VDI Opcode\# 102

See also \#VDI Inquire\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("vq_color") )
#include <vdi.h>

int vq_color( int handle, int color_index, set set_flag,
              int *rgb );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <color_index> is the color index (palette) to inquire.
  <set_flag> selects whether to return scaled values (0) or hardware
             values (1).  Scaled values are between 0 and 1000.
  <rgb> is a 3 entry int array to return the color values:
        [0] = red
        [1] = green
        [2] = blue


Function returns the RGB values for a palette color index.
The return value is <color_index> normally, or -1 if no such color
index exists.

\#VDI Opcode\# 26

See also \#VDI Inquire\#, \#vs_color\#(), \#Setcolor\#() and \#EsetColor\#(). 
\end

screen( capsensitive("vql_attributes") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vql_attributes( int handle, int *attrib);

