           [0] = interior style (see \#vsf_interior\#).
           [1] = fill color index (see \#vsf_color\#).
           [2] = fill pattern (see \#vsf_style\#).
           [3] = writing mode (see \#vswr_mode\#).
           [4] = border flag (see \#vsf_perimeter\#).


Function returns the area fill attributes.

\#VDI Opcode\# 37

See also \#VDI Inquire\#, \#v_bar\#(), \#v_circle\#(), \#v_contourfill\#(), \#v_ellipse\#(),
         \#v_ellpie\#(), \#v_fillarea\#(), \#v_pieslice\#(), \#v_rfbox\#() and \#vr_recfl\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vqt_attributes") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vqt_attributes( int handle, int *attrib);

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <attrib> is a 10 entry int array to return the text attributes:
           [0] = font ID (see \#vst_font\#).
           [1] = text color index (see \#vst_color\#).
           [2] = text angle (see \#vst_rotation\#).
           [3] = horizontal adjustment (see \#vst_alignment\#).
           [4] = vertical adjustment.
           [5] = writing mode (see \#vswr_mode\#).
           [6] = character width (see \#vst_height\#).
           [7] = character height.
           [8] = cell width.
           [9] = cell height.


Function returns the graphics text attributes.

\#VDI Opcode\# 38

See also \#VDI Inquire\#, \#v_gtext\#() and \#v_justified\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vqt_extent") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vqt_extent( int handle, char *string, int *extent);

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <string> is a NULL terminated text string.
  <extent> is an 8 entry int array to return a rectangle:
           [0] = x offset of first corner (lower left).
           [1] = y offset of first corner.
           [2] = x offset of second corner (lower right).
           [3] = y offset of second corner.
           [4] = x offset of third corner (upper right).
           [5] = y offset of third corner.
           [6] = x offset of fourth corner (upper left).
           [7] = y offset of fourth corner.


Function returns a rectangle which would enclose the given text string
if it were written using the current text attributes, including
rotation.  (The corners were listed in their un-rotated order.)

Offsets are defined relative to the alignment point.

\#VDI Opcode\# 116

See also \#VDI Inquire\#, \#vqt_f_extent\#(), \#v_gtext\#() and \#v_justified\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vqt_width") )
#include <vdi.h>

int vqt_width( int handle, char character, int *cell_width,
               int *left_delta, int *right_delta);

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <character> is a screen character.
  <cell_width> returns the cell width.
  <left_delta> returns the space between the cell wall and the
               character on the left side.
  <right_delta> returns the space between the cell wall and the
                character on the right side.


Function returns the cell width and alignment for a given character.
The return value is normally the character (cast as int), or -1 when
no such character exists.

\#VDI Opcode\# 117

See also \#VDI Inquire\#, \#v_gtext\#(), \#v_justified\#(), and \#vqt_advance\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vqt_name") )
#include <vdi.h>

int vqt_name( int handle, int element_num, char *name);

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <element_num> is font number (1,2, ... )
  <name> is a 32 (or 33) byte buffer array to return a NULL terminated
         string describing the font.
         When FSMGDOS or SpeedoGDOS is loaded, it also includes:
         [32] = flag (1 if proportional, 0 otherwise).


Function returns the name and index of a font given its element number.
The return value (font ID) is generally different from <element_num>,
or equals -1 when <element_num> exceeds the number of fonts loaded.

\#VDI Opcode\# 130

See also \#VDI Inquire\#, \#vst_load_fonts\#() and \#vq_vgdos\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vqt_fontinfo") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vqt_fontinfo( int handle, int *minADE, int *maxADE,
                   int *distances, int *maxwidth, int *effects);

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <minADE> returns the first ASCII character value.
  <maxADE> returns the last ASCII character value. 
  <distances> is a 5 entry array used to return:
              [0] = distance from bottom to baseline.
              [1] = distance from descent line to baseline.
              [2] = distance from baseline to half line.
              [3] = distance from baseline to ascent line.
              [4] = distance from baseline to top.
  <maxwidth> returns the maximum cell width (not including effects).
  <effects> is a 3 entry array used to return:
            [0] = additional cell width due to effects.
            [1] = additional offset on left side due to effects.
            [2] = additional offset on right side due to effects.


Function returns information about the font and how the current
effects affect the alignment (see \#vst_alignment\#).

\#VDI Opcode\# 131

See also \#VDI Inquire\#, \#v_gtext\#() and \#v_justified\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vq_cellarray") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vq_cellarray( int handle, int *pxyarray, int row_length,
                   int num_rows, int *el_used, int *rows_used,
                   int *status, int *colarray );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <count> is the number of x,y pairs.
  <pxyarray> is a four entry int array defining a rectangle (see
             \#VDI Coordinates\#:
             [0] = left x coordinate.
             [1] = lower y coordinate.
             [2] = right x coordinate.
             [3] = upper y coordinate.
  <row_length> is the number of cells per row (horizontal).
  <num_rows> is the number of rows (vertical).
  <el_used> returns the number of entries per row in <colarray>.
  <rows_used> returns the number of rows returned in <colarray>.
  <status> returns 0 normally, or 1 if a color could not be determined.
  <colarray> is an array[rows_used][el_used] used to return color
             indexes for each cell, or -1 when color not determined.


Function returns an array of color indexes corresponding to the
centers of a rectangular grid.

Note: This function is not required and may not be available on all
      devices (see \#VDI Description\#).
      It is NOT supported by the screen.

\#VDI Opcode\# 27

See also \#VDI Inquire\# and \#v_cellarray\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("vqin_mode") )
#include <vdi.h>

void vqin_mode( int handle, int dev_type, int *input_mode );

  <handle> is the \#VDI Handle\#.
  <dev_type> is the input device type:
             1 = locator (mouse or tablet)
             2 = valuator (optional)
             3 = choice (function keys)
             4 = string (keyboard)
  <input_mode> returns the input mode:
               1 = request (wait for event)
               2 = sample (return current state)


Function returns the input mode for an input device.

\#VDI Opcode\# 115

See also \#VDI Inquire\# and \#vsin_mode\#().
\end

