screen( "Signals" )
\#MiNT\# Signals                                                   <tos.h>
----------------------------------------------------------------------
 0  SIGNULL    can be sent but not delivered
 1  SIGHUP     hangup signal (window closed)
 2  SIGINT     sent by CONTROL-C
 3  SIGQUIT    sent by CONTROL-\\
 4  SIGILL     illegal 680x0 instruction
 5  SIGTRAP    trace trap (debugger tool)
 6  SIGABRT    abort signal (OS is crashing)
 7  SIGPRIV    privilege violation (see \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Supervisor Mode\#)
 8  SIGFPE     floating point error (divide by zero)
 9  SIGKILL    terminate signal (cannot ignore)
10  SIGBUS     bus error
11  SIGSEGV    memory protection violation
12  SIGSYS     bad argument to a system call
13  SIGPIPE    broken pipe
14  SIGALRM    clock alarm (see \#Talarm\#)
15  SIGTERM    software termination request
16  SIGURG     urgent condition on I/O channel
17  SIGSTOP    stop signal (cannot ignore)
18  SIGTSTP    sent by CONTROL-Z
19  SIGCONT    continue stopped process
20  SIGCHLD    child stopped or exited
21  SIGTTIN    read by background process
22  SIGTTOU    write by background process
23  SIGIO      I/O possible on a descriptor
24  SIGXCPU    CPU time exhausted
25  SIGXFSZ    file size limited exceeded
26  SIGVTALRM  virtual timer alarm
27  SIGPROF    profiling timer expired
28  SIGWINCH   window size changed
29  SIGUSR1    user defined signal 1
30  SIGUSR2    user defined signal 2

Note: Incompatible with definitions in <signal.h>
\end

screen( "MiNT System Keys" )
MiNT System Keys
----------------------------------------------------------------------
 0 = F1                11 = SHIFT F2          22 = RIGHT_ARROW
 1 = F2                12 = SHIFT F3          23 = LEFT_ARROW
 2 = F3                13 = SHIFT F4          24 = HELP
 3 = F4                14 = SHIFT F5          25 = UNDO
 4 = F5                15 = SHIFT F6          26 = INSERT
 5 = F6                16 = SHIFT F7          27 = CLR_HOME
 6 = F7                17 = SHIFT F8          28 = SHIFT UP_ARROW
 7 = F8                18 = SHIFT F9          29 = SHIFT DOWN_ARROW
 8 = F9                19 = SHIFT F10         30 = SHIFT RIGHT_ARROW
 9 = F10               20 = UP_ARROW          31 = SHIFT LEFT_ARROW
10 = SHIFT F1          21 = DOWN_ARROW

See also \#TIOCGXKEY\# and \#TIOCSXKEY\#,
\end

screen( "MINT.CNF" )
MINT.CNF File Format
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Commands:
  cd          change current directory
  echo        write comment to screen
  ren         rename file
  sln         create symbolic link (real path, link path)
  alias       create alias drive
  exec        execute program

System Variables:
  INIT        autoload TOS program
  GEM         autoload GEM program
  CON         redirect console I/O to file
  PRN         redirect printer output to file
  DEBUG_LEVEL MiNT debugging level (default = 0)
  DEBUG_DEVNO send debugging message to \#BIOS\# device
  SLICES      number of 20 msec timeslices per process (default = 2)
  MAXMEM      maximum RAM per process (default is unlimited)
  BIOSBUF     (Y/N) enable buffered I/O
\end

screen( "U:" )
Universal Directory
----------------------------------------------------------------------
In keeping with UNIX's device independent I/O protocol, MiNT creates
a pseudo drive (U:) in which almost everything is treated as a file or
sub-directory:

U:\\A to U:\\M correspond to disk drives A: to M:

U:\\DEV  contains all \#MiNT Device\# drivers
U:\\PIPE contains all \#MiNT Pipe\#s
U:\\PROC contains all \#MiNT Process\#s
U:\\SHM  contains all \#MiNT Shared Memory\# blocks
\end

screen( "MiNT Device" )
MiNT Loadable Devices
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Files in the \#U:\#\\DEV directory correspond to device drivers.
Opening one of these files is the same as opening a device, as in

  \#Fopen\#("PRN",1);
or
  \#Fopen\#("U:\\\\DEV\\\\PRN",1);

MiNT includes the following device drivers:
  AUX, CENTR, CON, CONSOLE, MIDI, MODEM1, MODEM2, MOUSE, NULL, PRN,
  SERIAL1, SERIAL2, STDIN, STDOUT, TTY

Additional device drivers can be installed using \#Dcntl\#(), or by
placing a driver file with an 'XDD' extension in the root or
'MULTITOS' directory and re-booting.

See also \#DEV_INSTALL\# and \#MiNT Device Number\#.
\end

screen( "MiNT Device Number" )
MiNT Device Numbers
----------------------------------------------------------------------
MiNT device numbers have no direct relationship with the BIOS drivers
in the \#BCONMAP\# array.

MiNT uses these device numbers for BIOS functions \#Bconout\#() etc. by
emulating the functions with calls to the \#*write\# etc. entries of the
\#DEVDRV\# structure.

These device numbers also have no direct relationship with the drive
numbers used by \#Dsetdrv\#() and \#Rwabs\#(), although every disk
drive has an associated MiNT device number.

See also \#Fxattr\#(), \#BIOS Device Number\# and \#I/O handle\#.
\end

screen( "MiNT File Mode" )
MiNT File Mode
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The 'mode' can be divided into bit fields:

mode & DEFAULT_DIRMODE = access code:
  S_IRUSR = read access to owner
  S_IWUSR = write access to owner
  S_IXUSR = execute access to owner
  S_IRGEP = read access to group
  S_IWGRP = write access to group
  S_IXGRP = execute access to group
  S_IROTH = read access to others
  S_IWOTH = write access to others
  S_IXOTH = execute access to others

mode & 0700 = special bits:
  S_ISUID = change effective user ID when executed.
  S_ISGID = change effective group ID when executed.

mode & S_IFMT = file type:
  S_IFREG = regular file
  S_IFCHR = BIOS special file
  S_IFDIT = subdirectory
  S_IFIFO = FIFO (pipe)
  S_IMEM  = memory region or process image
  S_IFLNK = symbolic link

See also \#Fchmod\#() and \#Fxattr\#().
\end

screen( "MiNT Pipe" )
MiNT Pipes
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Files in the \#U:\#\\PIPE directory correspond to system pipes.

A pipe is a FIFO (First In, First Out) buffer which can be used to
pass data between two processes.

Normally pipes are created using \#Fpipe\#(), and are assigned the
name "SYS$PIPE" with an extension corresponding to the decimal id
number.

One can redirect STDIN or STDOUT to a pipe using \#Fforce\#().
\end

screen( "MiNT Process" )
MiNT Process Files
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Files in the \#U:\#\\PROC directory correspond to processes.

When a process is open, it is assigned a filename corresponding to the
executable filename with a decimal process id for the extension.

The file size corresponds to the amount of RAM being used.
The time/date stamp corresponds to the elapsed time since the process
started (NOT the time/date when the process started).

The file attribute bits show the status of the process:
  0x00 = process is running
  0x01 = process is ready to run
  0x02 = process is a TSR (Terminate Stay Resident)
  0x20 = process is waiting for an event
  0x21 = process is waiting for I/O
  0x22 = process has exited
  0x24 = process was stopped by a signal

Reading this file corresponds to accessing process RAM starting at
the basepage.

See also \#Fcntl\#().
\end

screen( "MiNT Shared Memory" )
MiNT Shared Memory
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Any file created in the \#U:\#\\SHM directory is implemented as a RAMdisk,
which can be written to or read by any other process.  However, the
file will disappear after it is closed and the RAM is freed.

One MUST allocate RAM for the file using \#Fcntl\#(\#SHMSETBLK\#, ...)

See also \#SHMGETBLK\#.
\end

screen( "MiNT File System" )
MiNT Loadable File Systems
----------------------------------------------------------------------
MiNT is not limitted to disks or devices formatted with MS-DOS style
directories.

File system drivers can be installed using \#Dcntl\#(), or by
placing a driver file with an 'XFS' extension in the root or
'MULTITOS' directory and re-booting. 

Functions \#Dreaddir\#() and \#Fxattr\#() are used to search these
directories in place of \#Fsnext\#().

See also \#FS_INSTALL\#, \#FS_MOUNT\#, \#FS_UNMOUNT\# and \#FS_UNINSTALL\#.
\end

screen( "MiNT Version" )
MiNT Version Number
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... is given by the 'MiNT' cookie value:

  minor_version = value & 0xff;
  major_version = value >> 8;

e.g.: version 1.02 is stored as 0x102L

See \#Cookies\#, \#AES Version\#, \#GEM Version\# and \#TOS Version\#.
\end

screen( "kernel" )
MiNT kernel
----------------------------------------------------------------------
In keeping with UNIX nomenclature, the part of the MiNT operating
system which interfaces between I/O calls and the device drivers
is called the kernel.

The kernel is also responsible for process scheduling using timer
interrupts.
\end

screen( "FLOCK" )
File Lock                                           \#Fcntl Command Code\#
----------------------------------------------------------------------
typedef struct {
  int  l_type;   /* 0=read only, 1=write only, 2=locked, 3=unlocked */
  int  l_whence; /* offset relative to: 0=start, 1=current, 2=end   */
  long l_start;  /* offset to start of lock                         */
  long l_len;    /* length of lock (0 = rest of file)               */
  int  l_pid;    /* process id owning lock (filled automatically)   */
 } FLOCK;

See also \#F_GETLK\#, \#F_SETLK\# and \#F_SETLKW\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Fpipe") )
#include <tos.h>

int Fpipe( int *usrh );

  <usrh> is a 2 element array to return the pipe handles:
         [0] = read \#I/O handle\#
         [1] = write \#I/O handle\#


Function creates a pipe with the name "SYS$PIPE.ddd" (where 'ddd' is a
decimal number).

It returns 0 normally, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0x90

\#MiNT Opcode\# 256

See also \#MiNT\# and \#MiNT Pipe\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Fcntl") )
#include <tos.h>

int Fcntl( int f, long arg, int cmd );

  <f> is an open \#I/O handle\#.
  <cmd> is an \#Fcntl Command Code\#.
  <arg> and return value depend on <cmd>.


A negative return value is a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

Note: Fcntl SHOULD be typed as \link("%%GLOBAL%%")long\#, not \link("%%GLOBAL%%")int\#.
      You might want to modify the definition in <tos.h>.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 260

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Finstat") )
#include <tos.h>

long Finstat( int f );

  <f> is an open \#I/O handle\#.


Function returns the input status for a pseudo file.

It returns 0 normally, the number of characters waiting to be
read (int), or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\# (negative long).
It always returns 0 for a disk file.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 261

See also \#MiNT\# and \#U:\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Foutstat") )
#include <tos.h>

long Foutstat( int f );

  <f> is an open \#I/O handle\#.


Function returns the output status for a pseudo file.

It returns 0 normally, the number of characters available to be
written (int), or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\# (negative long).
It always returns 1 for a disk file.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 262

See also \#MiNT\# and \#U:\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Fgetchar") )
#include <tos.h>

long Fgetchar( int f, int mode );

  <f> is an open \#I/O handle\#.
  <mode> contains the TTY bit flags:
         1 = activate CONTROL characters
         2 = echo input characters


Function reads one character from a pseudo file.

It returns the ASCII character (0-255) in the low byte.
The console device will return \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Scan Codes\# in bits 16-23.
If bit 3 of the system variable 'conterm' is set, then bits 24-31 will
contain the value of the system variable 'kbshift' for that keystroke.
(Default is to clear bit 3 of conterm.)

\#MiNT Opcode\# 263

See also \#MiNT\# and \#U:\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Fputchar") )
#include <tos.h>

long Fputchar( int f, long c, int mode );

  <f> is an open \#I/O handle\#.
  <c> is the ASCII character (0-255) to be written.
  <mode> contains the TTY bit flags:
         1 = activate CONTROL characters
         2 = echo input characters


Function writes one character to a pseudo file.

It returns 1 normally, 4 if the character was written to a terminal,
0 if the character could not be written, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

Note: When writing to a terminal, <c> should include \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Scan Codes\# and
      kbshift values (see \#Fgetchar\#).

\#MiNT Opcode\# 264

See also \#MiNT\# and \#U:\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pwait") )
#include <tos.h>

long Pwait( void );


Function waits for any child process to stop or terminate.
It returns the process id (high word) and return code (low word)
from the next such child process, or 0 for no children left.

A process which was stopped by a signal returns 0x7F in bits 0-7 and
the signal value in bits 8-15.

A process which was terminated by a signal returns 0 in bits 0-7 and
the signal value in bits 8-15.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 265

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Signals\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pnice") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pnice( int delta );

  <delta> is priority decrement in arbitrary units.


Function adjusts the priority of the calling process.
Positive <delta> decreases priority; negative <delta> increases
priority.

It returns previous process priority. 

\#MiNT Opcode\# 266

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Prenice\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pgetpid") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pgetpid( void );


Function returns the process ID of the calling program.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 267

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pgetppid") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pgetppid( void );


Function returns the process ID for the parent process of the
calling program (0 = desktop).

\#MiNT Opcode\# 268

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pgetpgrp") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pgetpgrp( void );


Function returns the process group ID for the calling program.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 269

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Psetpgrp\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psetpgrp") )
#include <tos.h>

int Psetpgrp( int pid, int newgrp );

  <pid> is a process ID of a child process (0 = current process).
  <newgrp> is the process group ID to be assigned to process <pid>
           (0 = use <pid>).  Must be a positive number.


Function assigns a process group ID to a child process (or at least
a process sharing the same user ID).

It returns <newgrp> if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 270

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Pkill\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pgetuid") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pgetuid( void );


Function returns the user ID (0-255) for the calling program.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 276

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Psetgid\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psetuid") )
#include <tos.h>

int Psetuid( int uid );

  <uid> is the user ID to be assigned to the calling program.
        Must be a positive number from 1-255.


Function assigns a user ID to a process ONLY no ID has been
previously assigned (i.e.; current uid = 0).  User ID will be
inherited by all child processes.

It returns <uid> if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 272

See also \#MiNT\#, \#Psetpgrp\#() and \#Fchown\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pkill") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pkill( int pid, int sig );

  <pid> selects process(es) to be sent signal <sig>.
        Positive: <pid> = process ID.
        Negative: - <pid> = process group ID.
        0: Send signal to all processes in current group.

  <sig> is the signal to be sent (see \#Signals\#).


Function sends signals (which are usually fatal) to one or more
processes.

It returns 0 if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 273

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Psignal\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psignal") )
#include <tos.h>

void *Psignal( int sig, int *handler );

  <sig> is the signal to be intercepted (see \#Signals\#).
  <handler> is a function pointer (function name without "()") or:
            SIG_DFL = use default action.
            SIG_IGN = ignore signal.


Function can be used to change or reset the action taken by a
process when it receives signal <sig>.  Child processes inherit
signal handlers from their parents.

It returns the address of the old handler, or SIG_DFL or SIG_IGN,
or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 274


When <handler> is a function, it should be of the form

  cdecl void <handler>( long sig );

and must not make any \#AES\# or \#VDI\# calls.

Note: The signal will be automatically blocked while the handler
      is processing a previous occurance of the signal.

See also \#MiNT\#, \#Psigaction\#(), \#Psigreturn\#() and \#Psigblock\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pvfork") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pvfork( void );


Function creates a child process which is a duplicate of the
calling process.  Child process shares address space with the parent
(including the stack).  Parent waits until child process is done or
calls \#Pexec\#() in overlay mode.

It returns the process ID of the child to the parent process.
It returns 0 to the child process.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 275

See also \#MiNT\#, \#Pfork\#() and \#setjmp\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pgetgid") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pgetgid( void );


Function returns the group ID (0-255) for the calling program.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 271

See also \#MiNT\#, \#Psetgid\#() and \#Pgetegid\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psetgid") )
#include <tos.h>

int Psetgid( int id );

  <id> is the group ID to be assigned to the calling program.
        Must be a positive number from 1-255.


Function assigns a group ID to a process ONLY no ID has been
previously assigned (i.e.; current id = 0).  Group ID will be
inherited by all child processes.

It returns <id> if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 277

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Fchown\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psigblock") )
#include <tos.h>

long Psigblock( long mask );

  <mask> is a bit mask corresponding to new \#Signals\# to be blocked:
               0x1L blocks SIGNULL = 0
               0x2L blocks SIGHUP  = 1
                      ...
         0x4000000L blocks SIGUSR2 = 30


Function can be used to block one or more signals, but cannot unblock
previously blocked signals (new mask is OR'd to old mask).

It returns the previous mask value.

Blocked signals are queued until unblocked.
SIGKILL cannot be blocked.
Child processes inherit mask (unless launched by \#Pexec\#).

\#MiNT Opcode\# 278

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Psigsetmask\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psigsetmask") )
#include <tos.h>

long Psigsetmask( long mask );

  <mask> is a bit mask corresponding to the \#Signals\# to be blocked:
               0x1L blocks SIGNULL = 0
               0x2L blocks SIGHUP  = 1
                      ...
         0x4000000L blocks SIGUSR2 = 30


Function controls which signals are to be blocked or unblocked.
It returns the previous mask value.

Blocked signals are queued until unblocked.
SIGKILL cannot be blocked.
Child processes inherit mask (unless launched by \#Pexec\#).

\#MiNT Opcode\# 279

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Psigblock\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pusrval") )
#include <tos.h>

long Pusrval( long arg );

  <arg> is a user defined value assigned to a process, or
        -1L to keep current value.


Function assigns a value to a process.
It returns the previous value.

This value is reserved for use by programs (ignored by MiNT).
It is inherited by child processes.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 280

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pdomain") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pdomain( int newdom );

  <newdom> contains the new domain code:
            0 = TOS domain.
            1 = MiNT domain.
           -1 = keep current value.


Function can be use to change the process domain.
It returns the previous value.

The domain affects functions like \#Fread\#() and \#Fsfirst\#().

\#MiNT Opcode\# 281

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Fcntl\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psigreturn") )
#include <tos.h>

void Psigreturn( void );


Function must be used by signal handlers if they intend to terminate
by calling \#longjmp\#().

It should NOT be called under any other circumstances.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 282

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Psignal\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pfork") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pfork( void );


Function creates a child process which is a duplicate of the
calling process.

It returns the process ID of the child to the parent process.
It returns 0 to the child process.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 283

See also \#MiNT\#, \#Pvfork\#(), \#Pexec\#() and \#shel_write\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pwait3") )
#include <tos.h>

long Pwait3( int flag, long *rusage );

  <flag> is a bit mask:
         0x1 = return immediately.
         0x2 = include terminated processes.

  <rusage> is an array used to return info about stopped processes,
           or NULL:
           [0] = number of milliseconds used by code.
           [1] = number of milliseconds used by \#kernel\#.


Function (optionally) waits for a child process to be stopped (or
terminated) and returns execution times.

It returns the process ID of the child in the left 16 bits and the
exit code in the right 16 bits, or 0 if no child is currently
stopped (see <flag>).

  0xnn00 = exit code for process stopped by signal 'nn'
  0xnn7F = exit code for process terminated by signal 'nn'

\#MiNT Opcode\# 284

See also \#MiNT\#, \#Pwait\#() and \#Pwaitpid\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Fselect") )
#include <tos.h>

int Fselect( unsigned int timeout,
             long *rfds, long *wrds, long *xfds );

  <timeout> is the time in milliseconds to wait before aborting, or
            0L to wait indefinitely.
  <rfds> points to a bit map of \#I/O handle\#s for reading, or NULL.
         On return, the bit map will show which handles are ready.
  <wrds> points to a bit map of \#I/O handle\#s for writing, or NULL.
         On return, the bit map will show which handles are ready.
  <xfds> should be set to NULL.


Function waits for one or more \#I/O handle\#s to become unblocked.
It returns the number of handles unblocked (sum of bits set in *rfds
and *wrds), or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

Note: Does not currently function on any BIOS device except keyboard.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 285

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Pwait\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Prusage") )
#include <tos.h>

void Prusage( long *r );

  <r> is a long array used to return process information:
      [0] returns time spent in the MiNT \#kernel\#.
      [1] returns time spent by the process code.
      [2] returns time spent in the MiNT \#kernel\# for child processes.
      [3] returns time spent by child processes.
      [4] returns RAM used by process (in bytes).
      [5]-[7] are reserved for future use.

      All times are given in milliseconds.


Function returns resource usage information about the current process.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 286

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Psetlimit\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psetlimit") )
#include <tos.h>

long Psetlimit( int lim, long value );

  <limit> selects the type of limit specified by <value>:
          1 - maximum CPU time in msec.
          2 - maximum RAM size.
                    3 - maximum \#Malloc\#() size.
  <value> is the new limit value selected by <limit>, or
          0 for unlimited, or
          negative to leave the old limit unchanged.


Function modifies the resource allocation limits for the current
process.

It returns the previous value for the limit specified by <limit>.

Child processes inherit these limits.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 287

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Talarm") )
#include <tos.h>

long Talarm( long secs );

  <secs> is the time in seconds before receiving a SIGALRM signal, or
         0 to cancel a previous request, or
         negative to leave the current value unchanged.


Function requests a SIGALRM signal to be sent to itself after the
specified (real) time interval.

It returns the remaining time in milliseconds, or 0 if no alarm is
currently set (or less than 1000 msec remains).

\#MiNT Opcode\# 288

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Signals\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pause") )
#include <tos.h>

void Pause( void );


Function waits for a signal.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 289

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Signals\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Sysconf") )
#include <tos.h>

long Sysconf( int n );

  <n> selects the type of information to be returned:
      -1 = maximum legal value for <n>.
       0 = maximum number of memory regions per process.
       1 = maximum length of \#Pexec\#() command string.
       2 = maximum number of open files per process.
       3 = maximum number of supplementary group ID's.
       4 = maximum number of process per user.


Function returns information about the system configuration.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 290

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psigpending") )
#include <tos.h>

long Psigpending( void );


Function returns a bit map of signals which have been sent to the
current process but are being blocked:
      0x1L for SIGNULL = 0
      0x2L for SIGHUP  = 1
           ...
0x4000000L for SIGUSR2 = 30

\#MiNT Opcode\# 291

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Signals\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Dpathconf") )
#include <tos.h>

long Dpathconf( char *name, int n );

  <name> is a NULL terminated string containing a file system name
         (folder pathname).

  <n> selects the type of information to return:
      -1 = max. legal value for <n>.
       0 = internal limit on the number of open files.
       1 = max. number of links to a file.
       2 = max. length of a full path name.
       3 = max. length of an individual file name.
       4 = number of bytes that can be written atomically
       5 = information about file name truncation.
       6 = information about case sensitivity.

Function returns information about a given sub-directory.
The value 0x7FFFFFFFL is used to indicate no limit.

For <n> == 5 (file name truncation), it returns:
  0 = file names are never truncated.
  1 = file names are automatically truncated to max. length.
  2 = file names are automatically converted to MS-DOS file names
      (eight characters with 3 character extension).

For <n> == 6 (case sensitivity), it returns:
  0 = file names are case sensitive.
  1 = file names are converted to upper case.
  2 = file names are case insensitive, but are saved in the directory
      preserving their original case.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 292

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Pathnames\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pmsg") )
#include <tos.h>

long Pmsg( int mode, long mbox, \#MSG\# *msg );

  <mode> selects the function operation:
         0 = read message from <mbox>.
         1 = write message to <mbox> and wait until it has been
             read by another process.
         2 = write message to <mbox> and wait until a return
             message has been read.
         0x8000 = return immediately (bit flag).

  <mbox> is the message box number.
  <msg> is a buffer stucture (passed by address) to send or
        receive a message.


Function sends and/or receives a message from the specified message
box.

It returns 0 if successful, -1 if no process waiting for send or
receive a message (when not waiting), or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 293

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Fmidipipe") )
#include <tos.h>

long Fmidipipe( int pid, int in, int out );

  <pid> is the process ID, or 0 for the current process.
  <in> is the \#I/O handle\# to be assigned to MIDI input.
  <out> is the \#I/O handle\# to be assigned to MIDI output.


Function assigns I/O handles to the MIDI device.  (Actually, the
MIDI is already assigned I/O handles -4 [in] and -5 [out], although
these is no device name associated with these handles.)

It returns 0 if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 294

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Midiws\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Prenice") )
#include <tos.h>

int Prenice( int pid, int delta );

  <pid> is a process ID, or 0 for the current process.
  <delta> is priority decrement in arbitrary units.


Function adjusts the priority of the specified process.
Positive <delta> decreases priority; negative <delta> increases
priority.

It returns the previous priority, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 295

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Pnice\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Dopendir") )
#include <tos.h>

long Dopendir( char *name, int flag );

  <name> is a NULL terminated string containing the directory
         pathname (see \#Pathnames\#).
  <flag> selects the search mode:
         0 = normal mode (UNIX style file index).
         1 = compatibility mode (GEMDOS filenames).


Function opens a directory for reading by \#Dreaddir\#().

It returns a long directory handle if successful, or a
\#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.  Errors can be detected using:

    handle = Dopendir(name,flag);
  if((handle & 0xFF000000L) == 0xFF000000L) { /* error detected */

\#MiNT Opcode\# 296

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Dclosedir\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Dreaddir") )
#include <tos.h>

long Dreaddir( int buflen, long dir, char *buf );

  <buflen> is buffer size in bytes.
  <dir> is a directory handle returned previously by \#Dopendir\#().
  <buf> returns the name of the next file in the directory as a
        NULL terminated string.  In normal mode, it also returns
        a unique file index in the first four bytes of buf.

        Use \#memcpy\#() to copy the index to a long variable, or
        use a structure address for <buf> (cast as char*).


Function gets the next filename from an open directory.

It returns 0 if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#:
  -49 = no more files
  -64 = <buflen> not large enough.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 297

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\#, \#Drewinddir\#() and \#Fsfirst\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Drewinddir") )
#include <tos.h>

long Drewinddir( long dir );

  <dir> is a directory handle returned previously by \#Dopendir\#().


Function cause \#Dreaddir\#() to start at the beginning of the directory.
It returns 0 if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 298

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Dclosedir") )
#include <tos.h>

long Dclosedir( long dir );

  <dir> is a directory handle returned previously by \#Dopendir\#().


Function closes a previously opened directory.
There is a limit on how many directories can be open at a time.

It returns 0 if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 298

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Fxattr") )
#include <tos.h>

long Fxattr( int flag, char *name, \#XATTR\# *buf );

  <flag> selects how to treat links:
         0 = return attributes of linked file.
         1 = return attributes of link itself.
  <name> is a NULL terminated string containing the file's \link("Pathnames")pathname\#.
  <buf> is a structure buffer used to return extended attributes.


Function reads the extended attributes for a file.
It returns 0 if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 300

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\#, \#Fattrib\#() and \#Fdatime\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Flink") )
#include <tos.h>

long Flink( char *oldname, char *newname );

  <oldname> is a NULL terminated string containing an existing file's
            \link("Pathnames")pathname\#.
  <newname> is a NULL terminated string containing the link's
            \link("Pathnames")pathname\#.


Function creates a hard link.
Deleting one pathname will not affect the other.
Both pathnames must reside on the same physical device.

It returns 0 if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 301

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Fsymlink\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Fsymlink") )
#include <tos.h>

long Fsymlink( char *oldname, char *newname );

  <oldname> is a NULL terminated string containing an existing file's
            \link("Pathnames")pathname\#.
  <newname> is a NULL terminated string containing the link's
            \link("Pathnames")pathname\#.


Function creates a symbolic link.
Deleting the link's pathname removes the link.
Deleting the file's pathname will cause the link to fail.
Pathnames need not reside on the same physical device.

It returns 0 if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 302

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Flink\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Freadlink") )
#include <tos.h>

long Freadlink( int size, char *buf, char *name );

  <size> is the size of <buf> in bytes.
  <buf> is used to return the linked pathname.
  <name> is a NULL terminated string containing a symbolic link's
         \link("Pathnames")pathname\#.


Function gets the pathname refered to by a symbolic link.
It returns 0 if successful, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 303

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Dcntl") )
#include <tos.h>

long Dcntl( int cmd, char *name, long arg );

  <cmd> is the command code:
        0xDE00 = \#DEV_NEWTTY\#
        0xDE01 = \#DEV_NEWBIOS\#
        0xDE02 = \#DEV_INSTALL\#
        0xF001 = \#FS_INSTALL\#
        0xF002 = \#FS_MOUNT\#
        0xF003 = \#FS_UNMOUNT\#
        0xF004 = \#FS_UNINSTALL\#

  <name> is a NULL terminated string containing a pathname on the
         \#U:\# pseudo-drive.
  <arg> and the return value depend on <cmd>.


A negative return value is a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 304

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90
      Some command codes implemented with version 1.08

See also \#MiNT\#, \#MiNT Device\# and \#MiNT File System\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Fchown") )
#include <tos.h>

long Fchown( char *name, int uid, int gid );

  <name> is the pathname of the file to be modified.
  <uid> is the new user ID (old uid must be 0).
  <gid> is the new group ID (uid must be member).


Function assigns a new owner to a file.
It returns 0 normally, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 305

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Pathnames\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Fchmod") )
#include <tos.h>

long Fchmod( char *name, int mode );

  <name> is the pathname of the file to be modified.
  <mode> contains the new security flags:
         S_IRUSR = read access for owner
         S_IWUSR = write access for owner
         S_IXUSR = execute access for owner
         S_IRGRP = read access for group
         S_IWGRP = write access for group
         S_IXUSR = execute access for group
         S_IROTH = read access for others
         S_IWOTH = write access for others
         S_IXOTH = execute access for others
         S_ISUID = change effective user ID when executed
         S_IGUID = change effective group ID when executed


Function changes the security flags for a file.
It returns 0 normally, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 306

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.90

See also \#MiNT\#, \#MiNT File Mode\# and \#Pathnames\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pumask") )
#include <tos.h>

long Pumask( unsigned int mode );

  <mode> contains the new default security flags:
         S_IRUSR = read access for owner
         S_IWUSR = write access for owner
         S_IXUSR = execute access for owner
         S_IRGRP = read access for group
         S_IWGRP = write access for group
         S_IXUSR = execute access for group
         S_IROTH = read access for others
         S_IWOTH = write access for others
         S_IXOTH = execute access for others


Function changes the default security flags for all new files and
directories created by the process.

It returns the previous <mode> values.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 307

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.92

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Pathnames\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psemaphore") )
#include <tos.h>

long Psemaphore( int mode, long id, long timeout );

  <mode> selects the operation:
         0 = create semaphore
         1 = destroy semaphore
         2 = get semaphore
         3 = release semaphore
  <id> is a unique identifier.
  <timeout> is the time in milliseconds to wait (<mode> = 2 only), or
            0 to return immediately, or -1 to wait indefinitely. 


Function returns 0 if successful, or -1 if unsuccessful.

Semaphores can only be 'owned' by one process at a time, and are
used primarily to schedule access to resources.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 308

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.92

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Dlock") )
#include <tos.h>

long Dlock( int mode, int drive );

  <mode> is 1 to lock the drive, and 0 to unlock the drive.
  <drive> is the \#MiNT Device Number\#.


Function prevents other processes from accessing a device.
It returns 0 normally, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 309

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.93

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psigpause") )
#include <tos.h>

void Psigpause( unsigned long mask );

  <mask> is a bit mask corresponding to \#Signals\# to wait for:
               0x1L selects SIGNULL = 0
               0x2L selects SIGHUP  = 1
                      ...
         0x4000000L selects SIGUSR2 = 30


Function waits until one of the selected signals is received.
It returns AFTER the signal handler is done.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 310

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.95

See also \#MiNT\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Psigaction") )
#include <tos.h>

long Psigaction( int sig, \#SIGACTION\# *act, \#SIGACTION\# *oact );

  <sig> is the signal number (see \#Signals\#).
  <act> defines the default action for new signals.
  <oact> defines the action for any pending signals.


Function changes the default (SIG_DFT) signal handler for a signal.
It returns 0 normally, or a \#BIOS/GEMDOS Error Code\#.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 311

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.95

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Psignal\#().
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pgeteuid") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pgeteuid( void );


Function returns effective user ID of the current process.
The effective user ID differs from the user ID when executing a file
which has the S_ISUID mode bit set.

\#MiNT Opcode\# 312

Note: Implemented starting with \#MiNT Version\# 0.95

See also \#MiNT\# and \#Fchmod\#()
\end

screen( capsensitive("Pgetegid") )
#include <tos.h>

int Pgetegid( void );


Function returns effective group ID of the current process.
